1
00:01:15,321 --> 00:01:19,033
This is a true story about friendship
that runs deeper than blood.

2
00:01:20,034 --> 00:01:23,955
This is my story & that of the only 3
friends in my life who truly mattered.

3
00:01:25,498 --> 00:01:28,877
Two of them were killers who
never made it past the age of thirty.

4
00:01:29,752 --> 00:01:33,089
The other is a non-practicing attorney
living with the pain of his past...

5
00:01:33,590 --> 00:01:36,759
...too afraid to let it go,
never confronting its horror.

6
00:01:38,761 --> 00:01:42,557
I'm the only one who could speak for
them... and the children we were.

7
00:03:24,200 --> 00:03:25,994
My three friends and
I were inseparable...

8
00:03:26,536 --> 00:03:28,955
...happy and content to live in the
closed world of Hell's Kitchen.

9
00:03:29,539 --> 00:03:32,166
The West Side streets of Manhattan
were our private playground...

10
00:03:32,625 --> 00:03:36,880
...a cement kingdom where we felt we
were nothing less than absolute rulers.

11
00:03:39,632 --> 00:03:41,718
Hell's Kitchen was populated
by an uneasy blend of...

12
00:03:41,801 --> 00:03:43,761
Irish, Italian, Puerto Rican,

13
00:03:43,803 --> 00:03:47,390
and Eastern European labourers.
Hard men living hard lives.

14
00:03:57,984 --> 00:04:00,612
We lived in railroad apartments
inside red brick tenements.

15
00:04:01,321 --> 00:04:03,656
Few mothers worked and all had
trouble with the men they married.

16
00:04:11,331 --> 00:04:13,666
I buried one fucking wife,
I could bury another one!

17
00:04:20,215 --> 00:04:22,759
Domestic violence was a cottage
industry in Hell's Kitchen.

18
00:04:23,259 --> 00:04:25,470
Yet, there was no divorce
and few separations.

19
00:04:25,553 --> 00:04:27,555
The will of the Church was forceful.

20
00:04:28,264 --> 00:04:30,683
For a marriage to end,
someone usually had to die.

21
00:04:34,270 --> 00:04:35,855
Yet, despite the harshness of life...

22
00:04:36,481 --> 00:04:39,108
...Hell's Kitchen offered the kids
on its streets a safety net...

23
00:04:39,317 --> 00:04:40,818
...enjoyed by few other neighbourhoods.

24
00:04:42,403 --> 00:04:45,073
Crimes against people of the
neighbourhood were not permitted.

25
00:04:45,823 --> 00:04:48,159
When they did occur, the punishment
doled out was severe...

26
00:04:48,743 --> 00:04:50,078
...and, in some cases, final.

27
00:04:51,079 --> 00:04:54,082
A drug dealer from uptown
moved heroin into Hell's Kitchen.

28
00:04:54,832 --> 00:04:57,544
A packet killed the twelve-year old
son of a Puerto Rican numbers runner.

29
00:04:58,336 --> 00:05:00,338
It was the last packet
the dealer ever sold.

30
00:05:02,173 --> 00:05:05,218
Hell's Kitchen was a place of
innocence... ruled by corruption.

31
00:05:08,179 --> 00:05:10,890
My friends and I spent lots of time
inside Holy Angels.

32
00:05:10,932 --> 00:05:12,767
We each served as altar boys.

33
00:05:13,434 --> 00:05:15,228
Everyone wanted to work
funeral masses,

34
00:05:15,270 --> 00:05:17,188
since the funeral included a $3 fee...

35
00:05:17,605 --> 00:05:19,566
...and more if you looked
sufficiently somber.

36
00:05:21,609 --> 00:05:23,820
There was an active competition
between the four of us...

37
00:05:23,903 --> 00:05:25,572
...to come up with the best
and boldest prank.

38
00:05:27,031 --> 00:05:28,992
Two weeks into the new school year,

39
00:05:29,033 --> 00:05:31,035
I found the nun's clacker in
the school hallway...

40
00:05:31,327 --> 00:05:32,871
...and I was ready for the big leagues.

41
00:05:34,914 --> 00:05:36,916
In church, it was used to alert
the girls as to when...

42
00:05:37,083 --> 00:05:39,252
...they should stand, sit,
kneel and genuflect...

43
00:05:39,419 --> 00:05:41,671
...all based on the number of
times the clacker was pressed.

44
00:05:42,255 --> 00:05:44,924
In my pocket, it was cause for havoc.

45
00:05:54,475 --> 00:05:58,855
You will be defenders of the faith.
You will be soldiers of Christ.

46
00:05:59,856 --> 00:06:01,274
And you will receive the gifts...

47
00:06:01,816 --> 00:06:02,775
...of the Holy Spirit.

48
00:06:10,533 --> 00:06:11,993
It's gonna be a great day and your...

49
00:06:12,160 --> 00:06:15,496
...parents will be proud of you.
When you were baptised...

50
00:06:15,997 --> 00:06:18,333
...godparents made promises for you.
And now...

51
00:06:18,374 --> 00:06:20,293
-You're gonna confirm those promises.
-Let me have the clacker.

52
00:06:21,211 --> 00:06:22,462
What clacker?

53
00:06:22,629 --> 00:06:23,296
Now!

54
00:06:24,297 --> 00:06:25,840
Let everyone rise.

55
00:06:29,427 --> 00:06:30,303
Let us pray.

56
00:06:40,104 --> 00:06:41,940
Nuns are such easy targets.

57
00:06:43,983 --> 00:06:46,319
John and I spent more time in
church than the others.

58
00:06:46,653 --> 00:06:49,405
We were the only two in the group to give
any thought of entering the priesthood.

59
00:06:49,864 --> 00:06:52,325
And John and I were intrigued by
the powers the priest was given.

60
00:06:52,492 --> 00:06:54,869
A secret world of betrayal
and deceit, where people...

61
00:06:55,036 --> 00:06:57,622
...openly admitted dark misdeeds
and vile indiscretions.

62
00:06:58,039 --> 00:07:00,291
Confession was better than any
book we could get our hands on,

63
00:07:00,458 --> 00:07:02,669
or any movie we could see,
because the sins were real...

64
00:07:03,378 --> 00:07:04,504
...committed by people we knew.

65
00:07:05,296 --> 00:07:08,091
The temptation to be part of that
was far too great to resist.

66
00:07:08,258 --> 00:07:09,300
If we get caught, they'll burn us.

67
00:07:10,552 --> 00:07:11,886
What if our mothers are out there?

68
00:07:12,554 --> 00:07:14,514
What if we end up hearing
their confessions?

69
00:07:14,973 --> 00:07:16,224
What if we hear something worse?

70
00:07:16,891 --> 00:07:17,725
Like what?

71
00:07:17,934 --> 00:07:21,104
Like a murder. What if
somebody cops to a murder?

72
00:07:21,938 --> 00:07:25,608
Relax. All we've got to do is sit back,
listen and remember not to laugh.

73
00:07:33,658 --> 00:07:36,327
Seconds later,
our booth comes to life.

74
00:07:36,828 --> 00:07:38,955
I... sleep with married men.

75
00:07:40,582 --> 00:07:41,833
Men with families.

76
00:07:43,251 --> 00:07:47,088
In the morning, I tell myself
it's the last time, but it never is.

77
00:07:49,841 --> 00:07:50,967
Yes?

78
00:07:52,135 --> 00:07:55,471
You see, I'm... I'm pregnant.

79
00:07:59,058 --> 00:08:00,810
The father?

80
00:08:01,102 --> 00:08:02,145
Take a number.

81
00:08:03,021 --> 00:08:03,980
What are you going to do?

82
00:08:04,981 --> 00:08:06,524
I know what you want me to do.

83
00:08:07,442 --> 00:08:08,860
And I know what I should do.

84
00:08:10,486 --> 00:08:12,197
I just don't know what I'm gonna do.

85
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:16,409
Look, I gotta go.

86
00:08:17,327 --> 00:08:20,163
Thanks for listening, fellas.
I really appreciate it.

87
00:08:20,830 --> 00:08:22,373
I know you'll keep it to yourselves.

88
00:08:29,255 --> 00:08:30,089
She knew.

89
00:08:30,757 --> 00:08:32,008
Yeah, she knew.

90
00:08:32,383 --> 00:08:34,052
Why do you think she told us all that?

91
00:08:35,053 --> 00:08:37,722
I don't know. I guess
she had to tell somebody.

92
00:08:42,185 --> 00:08:44,604
Father Robert Carrillo was
a longshoreman's son...

93
00:08:44,771 --> 00:08:47,440
...who was as comfortable sitting on
a bar stool in a back alley saloon...

94
00:08:47,607 --> 00:08:49,734
...as he was standing at the altar
during High Mass.

95
00:08:50,443 --> 00:08:53,446
He had toyed with a life of petty
crime before finding his calling.

96
00:08:53,655 --> 00:08:56,282
He was a friend... a friend who
just happened to be a priest.

97
00:08:56,533 --> 00:08:57,867
You know what crap like
that does to your body?

98
00:08:58,368 --> 00:09:01,454
Come on, Father, it beats smoking.
And it's cheaper, too.

99
00:09:02,205 --> 00:09:05,416
Maybe.
So, what do you hear, anything?

100
00:09:06,084 --> 00:09:07,293
No, nothing.

101
00:09:07,460 --> 00:09:09,254
I hear you're interested
in becoming a priest.

102
00:09:09,629 --> 00:09:10,296
Who says?

103
00:09:11,464 --> 00:09:14,175
Word is you want to get the
feel of a confessional booth.

104
00:09:15,009 --> 00:09:16,553
I don't know what you're
talking about, Father.

105
00:09:16,928 --> 00:09:17,595
You don't?

106
00:09:18,721 --> 00:09:20,306
Maybe I got the wrong information.

107
00:09:20,849 --> 00:09:21,891
I guess you did.

108
00:09:23,685 --> 00:09:25,019
I'll see you later tonight.

109
00:09:25,603 --> 00:09:26,688
What's tonight?

110
00:09:27,605 --> 00:09:29,607
I gotta drop some books
and magazines off...

111
00:09:29,691 --> 00:09:31,609
...for the elderly and disabled
around the neighbourhood.

112
00:09:31,776 --> 00:09:32,944
Your mother said you'd love to help.

113
00:09:33,444 --> 00:09:34,612
I bet she did.

114
00:09:37,115 --> 00:09:40,785
Shakes... I don't want you
getting into any trouble.

115
00:09:41,327 --> 00:09:42,954
Come on, Father, you know I never do.

116
00:09:43,162 --> 00:09:45,164
That's all I wish for
you and your friends.

117
00:09:45,748 --> 00:09:46,374
That's it?

118
00:09:46,457 --> 00:09:48,209
That's it. Nothing else,
I swear, that's it.

119
00:09:48,626 --> 00:09:49,961
You know, a priest shouldn't swear.

120
00:09:50,670 --> 00:09:52,922
And kids shouldn't be listening
to other people's confessions.

121
00:09:53,006 --> 00:09:53,965
I'll see you tonight.

122
00:09:54,299 --> 00:09:55,133
All right... see you.

123
00:09:59,804 --> 00:10:02,056
Michael was the most sexually
experienced of our group,

124
00:10:02,223 --> 00:10:04,726
which meant that he kissed a girl
on more than one occasion.

125
00:10:05,268 --> 00:10:09,230
But his real love was Carol Martinez,
Hell's Kitchen's half-breed.

126
00:10:09,314 --> 00:10:12,317
Half Puerto Rican, half Irish,
she was raised by her father,

127
00:10:12,483 --> 00:10:13,860
her mother having died at childbirth.

128
00:10:14,319 --> 00:10:17,739
Carol stayed pretty much to herself but
was always comfortable in our company.

129
00:10:18,615 --> 00:10:19,657
We could always count on Carol...

130
00:10:19,741 --> 00:10:21,951
...to stand sentry on the first night
of the Ice Capades.

131
00:10:22,744 --> 00:10:24,704
While crowds of families lined
the front of the Garden...

132
00:10:24,787 --> 00:10:25,914
...waiting to see the skaters perform...

133
00:10:26,664 --> 00:10:28,333
...we each had one eye in a hole...

134
00:10:28,416 --> 00:10:30,960
...watching two dozen beautiful
and nearly naked women...

135
00:10:31,002 --> 00:10:32,462
...get into their skaters' outfits.

136
00:10:35,715 --> 00:10:37,258
This is what heaven must be about.

137
00:10:46,309 --> 00:10:47,769
Carol, you want to take a look?

138
00:10:48,603 --> 00:10:50,230
Like it's something I haven't seen?

139
00:10:50,897 --> 00:10:52,899
You're so lucky!

140
00:10:53,983 --> 00:10:58,446
She's so beautiful. My God, I could
die now and I wouldn't be sad.

141
00:10:58,821 --> 00:11:00,281
When my friends and I were young,

142
00:11:00,365 --> 00:11:02,367
...Hell's Kitchen was run
by a man named King Benny.

143
00:11:03,826 --> 00:11:06,788
When he was young, King Benny
was a hit man for Lucky Luciano.

144
00:11:07,121 --> 00:11:10,124
Lucky Luciano did a lot of good for
this country during World War ll.

145
00:11:10,291 --> 00:11:12,627
But you ain't gonna read about
that in any fucking history book!

146
00:11:13,253 --> 00:11:16,339
There was talk King Benny was
the shooter of "Mad Dog Coll"...

147
00:11:16,548 --> 00:11:20,468
...that prick on West 23rd Street.
He ran bootleg with "Dutch" Schultz.

148
00:11:20,969 --> 00:11:23,805
And he opened up a couple of clubs
with "Tough Tony" Anastasia.

149
00:11:24,055 --> 00:11:27,392
I was 14 when I first heard
about him. The story goes:

150
00:11:27,642 --> 00:11:29,519
As a kid, he wasn't much of anything.

151
00:11:30,687 --> 00:11:32,981
He was always getting the shit
kicked out of him in street fights.

152
00:11:33,356 --> 00:11:36,693
And then one day, and who the
fuck knows why, some Irish guy...

153
00:11:37,068 --> 00:11:40,738
...about 25 years old,
he takes King Benny...

154
00:11:40,905 --> 00:11:42,615
...and he flings him down
a flight of stairs.

155
00:11:42,949 --> 00:11:45,577
King Benny breaks all
his teeth in the front.

156
00:11:46,077 --> 00:11:47,245
You know what King Benny does?

157
00:11:48,329 --> 00:11:52,041
He waits. He waits 8 years...

158
00:11:52,208 --> 00:11:53,585
...to get even with that prick.

159
00:11:54,169 --> 00:11:56,045
He walks into a public bath house.

160
00:11:56,212 --> 00:11:57,338
The guy's soaking in the tub.

161
00:11:58,506 --> 00:12:02,552
King Benny takes out his front teeth.
He lays them down on the sink.

162
00:12:04,721 --> 00:12:06,514
Then he looks over at
the guy and says,

163
00:12:08,349 --> 00:12:11,561
"When I look in the mirror,
I see your face."

164
00:12:12,437 --> 00:12:13,771
Then he pulls out a gun...

165
00:12:15,231 --> 00:12:17,066
...and he shoots the guy twice
in each leg.

166
00:12:20,778 --> 00:12:21,779
Then he says to the guy:

167
00:12:22,447 --> 00:12:25,950
"Now, when you take
a bath, you see mine."

168
00:12:27,702 --> 00:12:29,787
No one ever fucked with
King Benny after that.

169
00:12:31,331 --> 00:12:32,123
Revenge!

170
00:12:34,042 --> 00:12:35,001
Revenge!

171
00:12:39,130 --> 00:12:40,131
Can I talk to you for a minute?

172
00:12:40,882 --> 00:12:43,676
I'd like to work for you.
Help you out, whatever you need.

173
00:12:44,344 --> 00:12:46,679
You're the butcher's kid... am I right?

174
00:12:49,265 --> 00:12:50,850
What kind of a job are you looking for?

175
00:12:51,226 --> 00:12:52,560
Whatever, it doesn't matter.

176
00:12:52,852 --> 00:12:54,604
It doesn't matter?

177
00:12:56,814 --> 00:12:58,942
Everybody says this is the
place to come for jobs.

178
00:12:59,484 --> 00:13:00,652
Who is everybody?

179
00:13:01,027 --> 00:13:02,529
People from the neighbourhood.

180
00:13:03,279 --> 00:13:06,616
Let me ask you, what
the fuck do they know?

181
00:13:07,450 --> 00:13:08,785
They know you got jobs.

182
00:13:14,541 --> 00:13:16,209
Sorry I wasted your time.

183
00:13:17,710 --> 00:13:18,795
Hold on a sec!

184
00:13:20,839 --> 00:13:22,507
Come back tomorrow if you want to work.

185
00:13:22,841 --> 00:13:24,509
-What time tomorrow?
-Any time.

186
00:13:24,717 --> 00:13:25,718
You'll be here?

187
00:13:26,344 --> 00:13:27,679
I'm always here.

188
00:13:35,228 --> 00:13:37,856
My first job for King Benny
paid $25 a week and...

189
00:13:38,022 --> 00:13:39,858
...ate up only 40 minutes of my time.

190
00:13:40,775 --> 00:13:43,653
In the dark club room, one of the guys
would hand me a crumpled paper bag...

191
00:13:43,820 --> 00:13:46,281
...and direct me to one of the two
local police precincts for delivery.

192
00:13:47,240 --> 00:13:48,825
It was a perfect way
to handle payouts.

193
00:13:49,367 --> 00:13:52,370
Come on, let's go! Right here.

194
00:13:52,537 --> 00:13:54,080
Let's see what kind of cash
you've got in that bag.

195
00:13:54,289 --> 00:13:56,416
You gotta be nuts! Do you
know who you're taking off?

196
00:13:56,791 --> 00:13:58,710
Yeah, we know, and
we're scared shitless.

197
00:14:00,086 --> 00:14:02,755
Give me the bag.
Give me the fucking bag!

198
00:14:02,922 --> 00:14:07,218
Hey, what you do there? Answer me!
What you do there?

199
00:14:07,760 --> 00:14:09,095
This time they took my money!

200
00:14:09,262 --> 00:14:10,763
You took the money from the boy?

201
00:14:10,930 --> 00:14:12,015
The money they took is in the bag.

202
00:14:12,223 --> 00:14:12,849
Let me have the bag.

203
00:14:13,057 --> 00:14:13,683
Fuck you!

204
00:14:15,226 --> 00:14:15,977
How about now?

205
00:14:16,227 --> 00:14:17,228
All right, take it easy.

206
00:14:17,312 --> 00:14:21,232
You're not smart anymore.
This make you stupid.

207
00:14:21,399 --> 00:14:22,358
Let me have the bag.

208
00:14:26,154 --> 00:14:27,071
Now, go!

209
00:14:27,322 --> 00:14:28,114
What about them?

210
00:14:28,281 --> 00:14:28,948
You care?

211
00:14:29,157 --> 00:14:31,826
Then go! Go! Run!

212
00:14:33,077 --> 00:14:35,663
I need somebody with me.
What if the old guy hadn't showed?

213
00:14:36,331 --> 00:14:37,332
What you need?

214
00:14:37,498 --> 00:14:38,833
My friends.

215
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:41,920
Your friends? What do
you think, this is camp?

216
00:14:42,086 --> 00:14:44,756
These kids, you can trust.
I've known them half my life!

217
00:14:46,508 --> 00:14:48,635
Okay, get your friends.

218
00:14:49,260 --> 00:14:52,430
Father Bobby knew we worked for
King Benny, and he wasn't pleased.

219
00:14:52,889 --> 00:14:55,517
He wasn't worried about the
pocket money, but the next step...

220
00:14:55,934 --> 00:14:57,268
...when they ask you to pick up a gun.

221
00:14:57,769 --> 00:14:59,312
He didn't want that to happen to us.

222
00:14:59,896 --> 00:15:01,773
You think running for King
Benny is a good idea?

223
00:15:01,940 --> 00:15:02,607
It pays.

224
00:15:02,899 --> 00:15:03,983
A lot of things pay.

225
00:15:04,067 --> 00:15:04,984
Not like this.

226
00:15:07,445 --> 00:15:09,614
Most priests liked to
preach from the pulpit.

227
00:15:10,073 --> 00:15:13,243
Father Bobby liked to talk during the
bump and shove of a pick-up game.

228
00:15:14,077 --> 00:15:14,869
Good shot!

229
00:15:17,121 --> 00:15:18,581
I found an art class for you to take.

230
00:15:18,748 --> 00:15:20,250
You know I can't afford
to take any art classes.

231
00:15:20,416 --> 00:15:22,669
You don't have to pay anything.
The teacher's a friend of mine.

232
00:15:23,336 --> 00:15:25,922
It could be nothing but
a waste of time, Father.

233
00:15:26,089 --> 00:15:27,841
Maybe, or it could be the first step.

234
00:15:28,091 --> 00:15:29,133
First step to what?

235
00:15:29,342 --> 00:15:30,343
Doing something with your life.

236
00:15:30,510 --> 00:15:32,011
You never know, it may
help you get out of here.

237
00:15:32,136 --> 00:15:32,929
You all can get out of here.

238
00:15:33,096 --> 00:15:34,848
Guys, are we gonna talk
or play basketball?

239
00:15:37,433 --> 00:15:39,018
Listen, I got a story
I want to tell you.

240
00:15:39,227 --> 00:15:41,855
It ain't the one about the lepers, is it?
Cause that one gave me nightmares.

241
00:15:42,063 --> 00:15:45,108
No lepers. Michelangelo.
He was born poor, just like you guys.

242
00:15:45,275 --> 00:15:46,734
He was a painter, he was a sculptor.

243
00:15:47,068 --> 00:15:50,405
He takes this job from the Pope.
Good money, good work.

244
00:15:51,614 --> 00:15:53,783
Okay, Father, but why'd
the Pope call him?

245
00:15:53,950 --> 00:15:56,119
Because the Pope was looking for
the best guy he could find...

246
00:15:56,286 --> 00:15:57,745
...to paint the ceiling
of his church in Rome.

247
00:15:57,954 --> 00:15:59,622
It don't sound like
that big a job, Father.

248
00:15:59,914 --> 00:16:01,249
Well, for Michelangelo it was.

249
00:16:01,708 --> 00:16:03,501
Michelangelo needed the job...

250
00:16:03,668 --> 00:16:05,628
...because it paid more money
than he ever had in his life.

251
00:16:06,337 --> 00:16:09,090
And that way, he could pay off the loan
sharks that were chasing his father down.

252
00:16:09,215 --> 00:16:09,883
What's his father?

253
00:16:10,675 --> 00:16:13,720
He was like a low-level... con guy.

254
00:16:13,887 --> 00:16:15,430
Conned people out of money,
goats, sheep...

255
00:16:15,513 --> 00:16:16,264
Goats?

256
00:16:16,431 --> 00:16:17,765
Chickens, whatever he could, you know.

257
00:16:17,932 --> 00:16:18,600
-Chickens?
-Chickens?

258
00:16:19,225 --> 00:16:19,976
You know what happened?

259
00:16:21,519 --> 00:16:23,271
He painted a ceiling no
one will ever forget.

260
00:16:23,521 --> 00:16:25,315
Painted it like he was touched
by the hand of God.

261
00:16:26,191 --> 00:16:27,400
Did he pay off the loans?

262
00:16:27,567 --> 00:16:28,693
Every single one of them.

263
00:16:29,861 --> 00:16:31,779
How long did it take him,
painting the ceiling and all?

264
00:16:31,946 --> 00:16:33,448
It took him about 9 years.

265
00:16:33,823 --> 00:16:34,866
9 years!?

266
00:16:35,158 --> 00:16:36,201
That's a big ceiling!

267
00:16:36,659 --> 00:16:39,329
I had a Puerto Rican do my
whole apartment in two days.

268
00:16:39,537 --> 00:16:40,455
And he had a bum leg.

269
00:16:40,830 --> 00:16:42,832
You know, I don't know what
I'm gonna do with you guys.

270
00:16:44,375 --> 00:16:46,711
Hey, just give us a job painting,
and leave the rest to us.

271
00:16:46,878 --> 00:16:48,004
You know what it was?
The Sistine Chapel!

272
00:16:48,338 --> 00:16:50,048
Sixteenth Chapel?

273
00:16:50,215 --> 00:16:51,007
Who painted the other fifteen?

274
00:16:59,641 --> 00:17:03,978
Outside events meant little. In a society
changing radically by the hour...

275
00:17:04,145 --> 00:17:06,898
...we watched the images scatter
nightly across the T.V. screens.

276
00:17:07,357 --> 00:17:10,485
Young protesters spoke about how they
were going to change our lives...

277
00:17:10,568 --> 00:17:14,239
...and fix the world. But while
they shouted their slogans...

278
00:17:15,323 --> 00:17:16,783
...my friends and I went to
funeral services...

279
00:17:16,866 --> 00:17:18,409
...for the young men
of Hell's Kitchen...

280
00:17:18,743 --> 00:17:20,870
...who came back from Vietnam
in body bags.

281
00:17:22,205 --> 00:17:24,666
We viewed with skepticism
the faces on television...

282
00:17:25,792 --> 00:17:28,211
...those protected by money and
upper-middle-class standing.

283
00:17:31,589 --> 00:17:34,509
A growing army of feminists
marched across the country...

284
00:17:35,218 --> 00:17:38,429
...demanding equality.
Yet, our mothers still cooked...

285
00:17:38,596 --> 00:17:41,266
...and cared for men who abused
them mentally and physically.

286
00:17:43,393 --> 00:17:46,229
For me and my friends, these
developments carried no weight.

287
00:17:47,146 --> 00:17:50,608
They might as well have occurred in
another country... in another century.

288
00:17:51,901 --> 00:17:53,361
Our attention was elsewhere.

289
00:17:54,153 --> 00:17:57,407
We sat with Father Bobby in a third
floor hospital ward, visiting John...

290
00:17:57,574 --> 00:17:59,075
...hoping he'd recover from
a punctured lung.

291
00:17:59,492 --> 00:18:02,078
A gift from one of his mother's
over-zealous boyfriends.

292
00:18:02,245 --> 00:18:05,582
I hope you like these.
You better not tell me you don't.

293
00:18:10,170 --> 00:18:12,463
Father Bobby didn't let
that situation rest.

294
00:18:12,672 --> 00:18:14,174
I gave on Sunday.
I'm in a rush, okay?

295
00:18:14,257 --> 00:18:14,883
John Reilly.

296
00:18:14,966 --> 00:18:16,301
The little punk!

297
00:18:16,843 --> 00:18:18,970
He got out of line, so I put him
back in line. No big deal.

298
00:18:19,137 --> 00:18:20,471
You put him in the hospital.

299
00:18:20,638 --> 00:18:24,142
He's alive, ain't he? Look, if he's
smart, he learned himself a lesson.

300
00:18:24,767 --> 00:18:26,769
What are you? About 220, 230?

301
00:18:28,021 --> 00:18:31,107
You're a big guy. How much
you think John Reilly weights?

302
00:18:31,941 --> 00:18:35,028
80, 85?
That's not even a featherweight.

303
00:18:36,154 --> 00:18:38,198
If this were a fight, you'd
be way out of your division.

304
00:18:38,489 --> 00:18:41,826
Look, it was a slap, it was nothing.

305
00:18:42,702 --> 00:18:44,412
Well, next time you'll be meeting me.

306
00:18:45,121 --> 00:18:48,917
And I may not be in your division, but
I do weight more than 85 pounds.

307
00:18:50,126 --> 00:18:52,795
And you won't need a doctor when
I'm done, you'll need a priest...

308
00:18:53,671 --> 00:18:55,006
...to pray over your body.

309
00:18:59,260 --> 00:19:00,595
See you in church.

310
00:19:06,518 --> 00:19:08,770
Father Bobby would've
made a good hit man.

311
00:19:08,937 --> 00:19:11,606
It's a shame we lost
him to the other side.

312
00:19:14,359 --> 00:19:17,737
We were down 7-6 in the last inning
of a sewer-to-sewer stickball game...

313
00:19:17,946 --> 00:19:20,406
...against Hector Maldonado...
and three of his friends.

314
00:19:21,950 --> 00:19:24,410
Come on, Davy... take this chump out.
He got nothing!

315
00:19:24,702 --> 00:19:25,370
Shut up!

316
00:19:25,954 --> 00:19:26,746
Who's that?

317
00:19:27,038 --> 00:19:28,081
His sister.

318
00:19:29,249 --> 00:19:29,916
What happened to her?

319
00:19:30,583 --> 00:19:33,253
I'm not sure, some kind of cancer
got in her legs or something.

320
00:19:33,461 --> 00:19:34,587
Worry about the game, come on.

321
00:19:36,089 --> 00:19:38,299
Come on, Davy, strike the scumbag out.

322
00:19:38,341 --> 00:19:40,677
He can't touch you Davy,
he can't touch you.

323
00:19:40,802 --> 00:19:42,971
Hey, while you don't got any
legs, you got a lot of tongue!

324
00:19:43,346 --> 00:19:44,556
This is it... home run!

325
00:19:46,099 --> 00:19:47,225
Easy, Mike.

326
00:19:48,101 --> 00:19:49,978
What the fuck you
looking at, little dick!?

327
00:19:50,979 --> 00:19:52,313
She's nothing but charm.

328
00:19:53,439 --> 00:19:54,774
Come on, Davy!

329
00:19:54,941 --> 00:19:56,276
You can take him,
you can take him, Mikey.

330
00:19:56,484 --> 00:19:58,611
Yeah, I told you he wasn't shit, baby!

331
00:19:58,862 --> 00:20:00,697
Hey, swallow your tongue,
you little gimp bitch!

332
00:20:01,030 --> 00:20:02,699
You could've helped her
across the street...

333
00:20:02,740 --> 00:20:03,950
...or you could've bought her
an ice cream.

334
00:20:04,075 --> 00:20:05,201
You didn't have to throw the game.

335
00:20:05,827 --> 00:20:07,620
Yeah, and now we're
the Salvation Army.

336
00:20:07,954 --> 00:20:09,956
You ever wonder why there
ain't a Salvation Navy?

337
00:20:10,290 --> 00:20:12,667
Game over, losers.
Cough up the cash. A buck each.

338
00:20:14,127 --> 00:20:15,086
He's no better than you.

339
00:20:15,753 --> 00:20:16,713
He was today.

340
00:20:16,963 --> 00:20:18,381
No. You let him be.

341
00:20:18,882 --> 00:20:21,926
All because Irish, here, has a thing
for little girls with no legs.

342
00:20:22,260 --> 00:20:24,095
Look, stay away from this,
fat man, all right?

343
00:20:24,679 --> 00:20:27,640
You boys are soft like bread.
It's going to catch up to you.

344
00:20:28,016 --> 00:20:29,976
And when it does, it's
going to hurt... bad.

345
00:20:30,268 --> 00:20:33,688
What happens is our business,
not yours, okay?

346
00:20:33,730 --> 00:20:35,231
You gotta stay tough to be tough.

347
00:20:35,648 --> 00:20:37,942
Guy smells it when you're weak;
eat you like a salad.

348
00:20:38,443 --> 00:20:39,485
Do you see that street?

349
00:20:39,569 --> 00:20:43,239
That street is the dish of life,
and you boys are appetisers.

350
00:20:43,406 --> 00:20:46,743
Somebody gonna come along, eat you
up and forget about you by dessert.

351
00:20:47,035 --> 00:20:49,329
Take it easy, fat man.
It was just stickball.

352
00:20:49,495 --> 00:20:52,665
Yeah, but going soft is a habit.

353
00:20:52,832 --> 00:20:56,169
You have to keep yourself mean
and cut your life around it!

354
00:20:56,336 --> 00:20:58,379
All right, all right, calm down.

355
00:20:58,463 --> 00:21:00,548
It's like hanging out with fucking
Confucius over here.

356
00:21:00,798 --> 00:21:02,133
Be funny, limp dick.

357
00:21:02,634 --> 00:21:04,469
Look, this is just free advice
from me to you.

358
00:21:04,511 --> 00:21:06,304
You take it or you throw it away.
It don't matter.

359
00:21:06,971 --> 00:21:08,306
Thanks a lot, fat man.

360
00:21:10,350 --> 00:21:12,810
In truth, we were all surprised
by Michael's actions.

361
00:21:13,311 --> 00:21:14,896
But in his mind,
losing that game meant...

362
00:21:14,979 --> 00:21:17,398
...handing a feeling of victory
to a girl in a wheelchair...

363
00:21:17,815 --> 00:21:19,400
...was more than the right thing to do.

364
00:21:29,077 --> 00:21:30,537
Come on, let's go swimming.

365
00:21:30,954 --> 00:21:32,956
The temperature topped out
at 98 degrees...

366
00:21:33,039 --> 00:21:35,250
...on the day our lives
were forever altered.

367
00:21:35,667 --> 00:21:38,378
I'm frying like an egg up here.
I say, we get some buttered rolls,

368
00:21:38,545 --> 00:21:40,755
a couple of cold sodas, and head
down to the docks.

369
00:21:40,922 --> 00:21:42,924
Can't you feel the breeze up here?

370
00:21:43,091 --> 00:21:45,009
What breeze?
We're surrounded by a wall, genius!

371
00:21:45,176 --> 00:21:46,094
The devil couldn't stand this heat.

372
00:21:46,177 --> 00:21:47,470
Will you guys shut up, please?

373
00:21:47,595 --> 00:21:48,763
I'm trying to get my burn.

374
00:21:48,930 --> 00:21:50,265
It's 98 degrees!

375
00:21:50,723 --> 00:21:53,017
-There's some breeze up here.
-It's a hot breeze.

376
00:21:53,101 --> 00:21:55,353
We haven't hit the hot dog
vendor in a couple of weeks.

377
00:21:56,020 --> 00:21:58,731
I don't know, Mikey. That cart guy
ain't like the others.

378
00:21:59,107 --> 00:22:02,777
I mean, he gets pretty pissed, like
crazy when you try to take him off.

379
00:22:02,944 --> 00:22:06,489
We can eat hot dogs...
or we can eat air... choose.

380
00:22:08,491 --> 00:22:10,159
Air is probably safer, Mike.

381
00:22:10,410 --> 00:22:12,620
Yeah, a hot dog ain't worth
bleeding over, Mikey.

382
00:22:12,996 --> 00:22:14,831
Yeah, anyway, whose turn is it?

383
00:22:15,331 --> 00:22:16,249
Yours!

384
00:22:16,749 --> 00:22:19,419
-Yeah, it's yours.
-Mine? It's not my turn.

385
00:22:19,669 --> 00:22:21,254
-Yes, it is!
-I went like last month.

386
00:22:21,421 --> 00:22:22,422
-He went two weeks.
-You never went.

387
00:22:22,589 --> 00:22:24,591
-Last month.
-Are you nuts? I went right after him.

388
00:22:24,757 --> 00:22:25,425
I'm not going.

389
00:22:25,633 --> 00:22:26,593
-Why?
-It's too hot.

390
00:22:26,968 --> 00:22:28,678
If I walk down the
stairs, I'll pass out.

391
00:22:32,432 --> 00:22:34,142
Mustard and onions. No soda.

392
00:22:34,684 --> 00:22:35,768
I know you!

393
00:22:36,269 --> 00:22:37,604
I look like a lot of people.

394
00:22:38,646 --> 00:22:39,772
The scam was simple.

395
00:22:40,356 --> 00:22:43,359
I was to walk up to the hot dog
vendor and order what I wanted.

396
00:22:43,902 --> 00:22:47,197
The vendor would then hand me my hot
dog and watch as I ran off without paying.

397
00:22:47,780 --> 00:22:50,533
This left the vendor with two
choices, neither very appealing.

398
00:22:51,075 --> 00:22:54,162
He could stand his ground and swallow
his loss, or he could give chase.

399
00:22:54,829 --> 00:22:56,497
The second forces him
to abandon the cart...

400
00:22:56,664 --> 00:22:58,583
...where my friends could
feast in his absence.

401
00:23:01,878 --> 00:23:03,463
I'm gonna need two napkins?

402
00:23:05,423 --> 00:23:06,758
Pay my money, thief!

403
00:23:14,390 --> 00:23:15,350
Wow! Ketchup!

404
00:23:15,433 --> 00:23:16,768
I took it from him and ran!

405
00:23:17,185 --> 00:23:21,022
I scooted past Tommy Mug's Dry
Cleaners and Armond's Shoe Repair.

406
00:23:21,773 --> 00:23:25,693
The vendor gave chase, a wooden-
handled, pronged fork in one hand.

407
00:23:27,445 --> 00:23:28,279
You gonna give me two?

408
00:23:39,082 --> 00:23:40,750
You know, these things are
heavier than they look.

409
00:23:40,959 --> 00:23:43,920
Genius, it's the gas tanks
to keep the food hot.

410
00:23:44,128 --> 00:23:45,421
They're heavier than shit!

411
00:23:46,214 --> 00:23:47,757
Think we can push it, the three of us?

412
00:23:48,716 --> 00:23:49,801
Push it where?

413
00:23:50,385 --> 00:23:53,054
A couple of blocks. It'll be
a nice surprise for the guy...

414
00:23:53,388 --> 00:23:55,890
...when he comes back from chasing
Shakes, not to find his cart.

415
00:24:17,245 --> 00:24:19,122
The vendor tired at 47th and 9th.

416
00:24:19,581 --> 00:24:21,124
I was on the other side of the street.

417
00:24:23,209 --> 00:24:25,211
He was beat... but not beaten.

418
00:24:26,045 --> 00:24:28,298
He could go ten minutes
more, just on hate alone.

419
00:24:28,798 --> 00:24:32,051
Give it up.

420
00:24:45,398 --> 00:24:46,232
What's wrong, Mikey?

421
00:24:47,400 --> 00:24:50,361
Shakes is taking too long.
He should've been back by now.

422
00:24:51,237 --> 00:24:53,031
He'll be fine. He's Shakes.

423
00:24:56,075 --> 00:24:58,203
You guys were supposed to take
the hot dogs, not the wagon.

424
00:24:58,912 --> 00:25:00,747
-Now he tells us.
-He's coming fast, Mikey.

425
00:25:00,914 --> 00:25:01,873
He still near?

426
00:25:02,582 --> 00:25:04,417
I got a plan! Come on
over by the subway!

427
00:25:05,502 --> 00:25:09,005
The plan was as simple and as dumb
as anything we had ever done.

428
00:25:09,923 --> 00:25:12,091
We were to hold the cart on the top
edge of the stairwell,

429
00:25:12,175 --> 00:25:14,427
Leaning it downward,
and wait for the vendor.

430
00:25:14,636 --> 00:25:16,554
We were to let it go the second
he grabbed the handles.

431
00:25:16,721 --> 00:25:19,891
Then we'd leave the scene as he struggled
to ease the cart back onto the sidewalk.

432
00:25:20,475 --> 00:25:22,644
To this day, I don't
know why we did it.

433
00:25:23,102 --> 00:25:24,562
But, we would all pay a price.

434
00:25:25,355 --> 00:25:29,275
It only took a minute... but
in that minute... everything changed.

435
00:25:30,568 --> 00:25:31,528
Guys, I can't hold it!

436
00:25:31,694 --> 00:25:33,404
-Don't let go!
-I can't hold it!

437
00:25:35,740 --> 00:25:36,449
I can't hold it!

438
00:25:50,129 --> 00:25:52,090
Stop! God, no! !

439
00:26:14,863 --> 00:26:15,697
Damn!

440
00:26:21,202 --> 00:26:25,081
Sweet Jesus! What have you boys done?

441
00:26:25,415 --> 00:26:28,168
What in the name of God
have you boys done?

442
00:26:28,251 --> 00:26:29,586
I think we just killed a man.

443
00:26:35,133 --> 00:26:38,219
While James Caldwell was slowly
recovering at St. Clare's Hospital...

444
00:26:39,012 --> 00:26:42,807
...we were charged and remanded
into our parents' custody.

445
00:26:43,850 --> 00:26:44,767
I'm sorry, dad.

446
00:26:45,143 --> 00:26:46,477
'Sorry' ain't gonna do you much good.

447
00:26:48,188 --> 00:26:50,815
Take it easy!
This is no time to get crazy!

448
00:26:52,066 --> 00:26:54,402
You're going to jail and you don't
even know what the fuck that means!

449
00:26:54,569 --> 00:26:56,196
Mom, tell him to calm down, mom!

450
00:26:56,404 --> 00:26:58,698
Mario, stop it!

451
00:26:58,865 --> 00:27:01,367
He's just a kid!
He shouldn't have to do time!

452
00:27:01,534 --> 00:27:06,039
Nobody in this family should have to do
time. I done enough time for everybody!

453
00:27:32,106 --> 00:27:33,525
I hear you're short an altar boy.

454
00:27:37,570 --> 00:27:38,571
You still remember what to do?

455
00:27:40,114 --> 00:27:42,784
Easy on the water,
heavy on the wine.

456
00:27:43,743 --> 00:27:45,995
And ring the bells whenever
I see someone start to nod off.

457
00:27:47,205 --> 00:27:48,957
Get ready... we got 5 minutes
till show time.

458
00:28:02,178 --> 00:28:03,471
I'm gonna miss this.

459
00:28:06,724 --> 00:28:08,017
I'm gonna miss all of this.

460
00:28:10,019 --> 00:28:13,481
I've been doing all I can, but so
far every door I touch is locked.

461
00:28:18,361 --> 00:28:21,739
I could run... we all could run.

462
00:28:24,868 --> 00:28:26,077
Disappear for a while.

463
00:28:27,412 --> 00:28:28,454
Nobody's gonna come looking.

464
00:28:30,290 --> 00:28:34,586
Nobody's gonna care about us...
about where we go.

465
00:28:40,216 --> 00:28:42,886
You run now, you're gonna
run till you die.

466
00:28:45,471 --> 00:28:48,641
Hiding's not gonna make it go away.
People aren't gonna forget.

467
00:28:51,102 --> 00:28:52,270
You've gotta face this.

468
00:28:58,693 --> 00:28:59,777
I can't, Father.

469
00:29:02,447 --> 00:29:03,865
I don't want to face it.

470
00:29:06,117 --> 00:29:07,744
I'm too scared to face it.

471
00:29:09,787 --> 00:29:10,872
I'm scared, too.

472
00:29:11,831 --> 00:29:15,835
Nobody's more scared than I am,
but you gotta do it.

473
00:29:19,297 --> 00:29:22,800
You're gonna be okay. You're
gonna make it through there.

474
00:29:24,385 --> 00:29:25,220
You understand?

475
00:29:31,017 --> 00:29:32,560
Come on. We got an audience.

476
00:29:40,401 --> 00:29:43,029
I counted three rummies and
four widows on my way in.

477
00:29:45,865 --> 00:29:48,409
Plus Fat Ralphie sleeping
one off in the last row.

478
00:29:50,328 --> 00:29:52,747
It's the rain. Bad weather
always brings in the crowds.

479
00:29:59,003 --> 00:30:00,338
This is one of my favourites.

480
00:30:01,673 --> 00:30:02,674
What is?

481
00:30:04,467 --> 00:30:08,429
"Whatever you do to the least of
my brethren... you do to me."

482
00:30:13,226 --> 00:30:14,102
Come on.

