507
00:31:35,433 --> 00:31:37,936
...I would've sentenced you to
a much stiffer punishment.

508
00:31:39,020 --> 00:31:41,356
I still have my doubts as to
your inherent goodness.

509
00:31:41,773 --> 00:31:44,025
Only time will serve to prove me wrong.

510
00:31:47,529 --> 00:31:48,863
Could you do me a favour?

511
00:31:49,531 --> 00:31:50,406
What do you want? Name it.

512
00:31:51,241 --> 00:31:52,784
The past couple of weeks...

513
00:31:52,867 --> 00:31:55,537
...my mother and father looked like
they were ready to kill each other.

514
00:31:56,204 --> 00:31:57,539
Could you watch over them for me?

515
00:31:57,705 --> 00:31:58,581
I will.

516
00:31:59,749 --> 00:32:03,086
And no matter what you hear,
tell them I'm doing okay.

517
00:32:03,962 --> 00:32:04,963
You mean, you want me to lie?

518
00:32:06,881 --> 00:32:09,634
It's a good lie, Father.
You can do it.

519
00:32:12,929 --> 00:32:13,930
Come on, let's go.

520
00:32:15,849 --> 00:32:16,766
Be strong.

521
00:32:17,308 --> 00:32:18,142
I will.

522
00:32:55,805 --> 00:32:59,142
The Wilkinson Home for Boys
held 780 youthful offenders...

523
00:32:59,684 --> 00:33:01,227
...housed in 5 separate units.

524
00:33:01,853 --> 00:33:04,814
From the outside, the facility
resembled what those who ran it...

525
00:33:04,856 --> 00:33:06,316
...wanted it to resemble...

526
00:33:07,066 --> 00:33:09,194
...some kind of nice
school or university.

527
00:33:11,196 --> 00:33:14,574
Michael, Tommy, John and I were
assigned to the 2nd floor of Group C.

528
00:33:15,408 --> 00:33:19,662
We each had a private 12 ft room.
I'd been in my room less than an hour...

529
00:33:20,205 --> 00:33:23,541
...when the panic set in.
It doesn't take very long...

530
00:33:23,708 --> 00:33:26,544
...to know how tough a person you are,
or how strong you can be.

531
00:33:27,420 --> 00:33:31,549
I knew from my first day at Wilkinson
that I was neither tough nor strong.

532
00:33:43,436 --> 00:33:44,771
Hello, Carcaterra.

533
00:33:46,773 --> 00:33:47,941
Toss your clothes on the floor.

534
00:33:49,067 --> 00:33:49,734
Here?

535
00:33:50,401 --> 00:33:52,153
Were you expecting a dressing room?
We don't have any.

536
00:33:52,445 --> 00:33:53,279
Now, lose the clothes.

537
00:33:54,113 --> 00:33:55,156
In front of you?

538
00:34:04,123 --> 00:34:04,916
Let's go, let's go!

539
00:34:16,010 --> 00:34:18,304
What's that piece of shit
around your neck? Take it off.

540
00:34:19,013 --> 00:34:20,932
It's Mary, you know, the mother of God.

541
00:34:20,974 --> 00:34:24,310
I don't give a fuck whose
mother it is. Take it off.

542
00:34:37,031 --> 00:34:38,032
Everything.

543
00:34:39,075 --> 00:34:40,702
You want me to stand here naked?

544
00:34:40,869 --> 00:34:41,995
Now you're catching on.

545
00:34:42,787 --> 00:34:45,540
I knew you Hell's Kitchen boys
weren't as dumb as everyone says.

546
00:34:53,131 --> 00:34:54,465
Now, what?

547
00:34:57,385 --> 00:34:58,303
Get dressed.

548
00:35:03,641 --> 00:35:05,852
There were four guards
assigned to each floor...

549
00:35:06,019 --> 00:35:09,355
...with one -- in our case, Nokes --
designated group leader.

550
00:35:11,191 --> 00:35:13,860
Ferguson was the only son of a
slain New York State trooper...

551
00:35:13,943 --> 00:35:15,945
...and was on the waiting list
for both the New York City...

552
00:35:16,029 --> 00:35:17,280
...and Suffolk County Police Departments.

553
00:35:18,031 --> 00:35:21,784
Styler was using his job at Wilkinson's
to finance his way through law school.

554
00:35:22,827 --> 00:35:24,871
Addison was a graduate of
a local high school...

555
00:35:25,038 --> 00:35:27,081
...who wanted nothing more
than a steady job that paid well.

556
00:35:28,416 --> 00:35:31,544
It was not a group of innocent
young boys at Wilkinson.

557
00:35:32,086 --> 00:35:33,880
Most, if not all, the inmates
belonged there.

558
00:35:34,130 --> 00:35:36,799
A number of them were riding out
their 2nd and 3rd convictions.

559
00:35:37,091 --> 00:35:40,595
All were violent offenders. Few seemed
sorry about what they had done.

560
00:35:41,262 --> 00:35:44,098
And as for rehabilitation,
forget it.

561
00:36:20,218 --> 00:36:22,220
What the fuck did you do that for?

562
00:36:23,721 --> 00:36:25,056
You got close to me.

563
00:36:25,348 --> 00:36:26,224
So?

564
00:36:27,141 --> 00:36:28,476
It bothers me.

565
00:36:29,477 --> 00:36:32,397
I don't want to be near you
or your creeped out friends!

566
00:37:28,620 --> 00:37:31,164
You know your time here
hasn't taught you shit!

567
00:37:32,916 --> 00:37:35,251
You're still the same fucking
bunch of clowns you were...

568
00:37:35,418 --> 00:37:37,003
...the day you walked in here.

569
00:37:39,130 --> 00:37:43,259
Okay, everybody go on back
and finish your lunches.

570
00:37:43,468 --> 00:37:44,427
There's nothing to see.

571
00:37:46,095 --> 00:37:48,348
Go on, go, sit down...
get out of here.

572
00:37:50,934 --> 00:37:51,809
Go on.

573
00:38:02,529 --> 00:38:03,530
That go for me too?

574
00:38:04,197 --> 00:38:05,532
No, it don't go for you.

575
00:38:06,032 --> 00:38:10,411
You go back to your room.
You're through with your lunch. Go on.

576
00:38:12,288 --> 00:38:15,208
You and me... we're gonna finish
this sometime real soon.

577
00:38:15,708 --> 00:38:16,668
Maybe at dinner.

578
00:38:16,876 --> 00:38:21,256
So... you Hell's Kitchen
boys get any lunch?

579
00:38:23,925 --> 00:38:25,051
I got to smell it.

580
00:38:26,553 --> 00:38:28,388
You got to smell it...

581
00:38:31,933 --> 00:38:32,725
That's good.

582
00:38:34,310 --> 00:38:35,186
Where you going?

583
00:38:36,104 --> 00:38:37,230
You said to get lunch.

584
00:38:38,189 --> 00:38:41,276
You boys don't need to get back
in line to get lunch 'cause...

585
00:38:41,442 --> 00:38:43,778
...there's plenty to eat right
where you're standing.

586
00:38:44,737 --> 00:38:45,947
You could smell it.

587
00:38:51,703 --> 00:38:52,787
I'm not hungry.

588
00:38:53,913 --> 00:38:56,082
Well, I don't give a fuck
if you're hungry or not.

589
00:38:56,916 --> 00:38:58,918
You eat... because I'm
telling you to eat.

590
00:39:03,882 --> 00:39:05,216
I'm still not hungry.

591
00:39:11,431 --> 00:39:13,391
I'll tell you when
you're hungry or not.

592
00:39:13,558 --> 00:39:14,434
Now, eat.

593
00:39:17,645 --> 00:39:20,148
Excuse me? What the
fuck are you looking at?

594
00:39:20,732 --> 00:39:24,569
Get the fuck down on your knees
now and finish your goddam lunch!

595
00:39:26,154 --> 00:39:29,616
Come on now, eat! Don't think you
got all fucking day, here! Eat!

596
00:39:30,033 --> 00:39:33,828
You've got some mashed potatoes...
come on, suck up some of that jello.

597
00:39:33,995 --> 00:39:37,832
Come on now, you fucking assholes, eat!
Don't be thinking you got all day.

598
00:39:37,999 --> 00:39:39,792
Hurry up. Come on, now, let's go.

599
00:39:41,002 --> 00:39:45,673
None of you clowns are leaving here until
these assholes finish their goddam lunch!

600
00:39:45,840 --> 00:39:48,968
You got that? Hey you...

601
00:39:49,135 --> 00:39:52,096
There you go, you can't have a good
lunch without a nice piece of bread. Eat!

602
00:39:53,973 --> 00:39:55,433
Come on now, that's good.

603
00:39:56,184 --> 00:39:58,019
Show the boys how you follow my rules.

604
00:39:58,228 --> 00:40:00,522
Rules! You understand?

605
00:40:01,689 --> 00:40:04,359
Hey look, boys, see how
he follows my rules?

606
00:40:05,235 --> 00:40:06,277
Your shift's over, Nokes.

607
00:40:08,738 --> 00:40:11,032
I'm not ready to go yet.
I still got a few more things...

608
00:40:11,199 --> 00:40:13,326
...I gotta clean up here
before I can leave.

609
00:40:13,493 --> 00:40:16,538
It's my tour now.
I'll clean what needs cleaning.

610
00:40:16,704 --> 00:40:18,540
Stay out of this one. It's got
nothing to do with you.

611
00:40:19,332 --> 00:40:21,709
This one, I'm staying in.

612
00:40:26,214 --> 00:40:27,549
Don't fuck with me, boy.

613
00:40:29,592 --> 00:40:32,762
No, Nokes... you fuck with me.

614
00:40:34,430 --> 00:40:35,765
I'm asking you.

615
00:40:42,772 --> 00:40:44,232
You're eating into my shift.

616
00:40:47,360 --> 00:40:50,738
I'll get out of your way... for now.

617
00:40:51,990 --> 00:40:53,533
I'll take what I can get.

618
00:40:56,411 --> 00:40:57,745
You boys get off your knees.

619
00:41:11,593 --> 00:41:13,720
It's a tragedy. I'll tell you.

620
00:41:15,221 --> 00:41:17,599
I don't understand you boys.

621
00:41:17,640 --> 00:41:19,893
I don't think you know what
it means to have rules.

622
00:41:20,059 --> 00:41:22,228
You gotta have rules,
and you gotta have discipline.

623
00:41:23,021 --> 00:41:25,690
I don't know what it was like in your
homes and your home lives, but...

624
00:41:26,149 --> 00:41:29,485
...in my house with my father,
there were rules!

625
00:41:29,819 --> 00:41:32,864
And if you didn't follow the
rules, there was hell to pay.

626
00:41:33,615 --> 00:41:36,284
You had rules, and you had discipline.

627
00:41:37,911 --> 00:41:42,415
Sometimes, it wasn't nice, but
we learned. We sure did learn.

628
00:41:44,584 --> 00:41:47,253
Right around there to the right.
There you go.

629
00:41:53,760 --> 00:41:58,389
I mean, it's a simple thing, really.
You got rules, and you got discipline.

630
00:41:59,140 --> 00:42:01,809
That's the beginning of the story,
and that's the end of the story.

631
00:42:09,150 --> 00:42:10,276
We understand each other?

632
00:42:11,152 --> 00:42:12,278
Turn and face the wall.

633
00:42:21,704 --> 00:42:24,958
Now, we got interrupted earlier
in the lunch room, but...

634
00:42:26,042 --> 00:42:27,836
...there's no one
to interrupt us here now.

635
00:42:38,680 --> 00:42:39,597
What do you want?

636
00:42:41,891 --> 00:42:43,226
A blow job.

637
00:42:51,693 --> 00:42:52,694
Down on your knees.

638
00:42:56,614 --> 00:42:58,616
Face the wall.

639
00:43:15,425 --> 00:43:18,386
There are no clear pictures of
the sexual abuse we endured.

640
00:43:18,928 --> 00:43:21,097
I buried it as deep as
it could possibly go.

641
00:43:22,223 --> 00:43:24,851
What I remember most clearly
from that chilly October night...

642
00:43:24,934 --> 00:43:26,436
...was that it was
my fourteenth birthday...

643
00:43:27,312 --> 00:43:28,938
...and the end of my childhood.

644
00:43:39,115 --> 00:43:42,118
Early in my stay, I'd written and
asked my father not to come.

645
00:43:42,952 --> 00:43:45,288
I couldn't look at my father
and have him see on my face...

646
00:43:45,455 --> 00:43:46,414
...all that had happened to me.

647
00:43:47,123 --> 00:43:49,959
Michael had done the same with the
interested members of his family.

648
00:43:50,126 --> 00:43:52,128
Tommy's mother couldn't get
it together to visit.

649
00:43:52,420 --> 00:43:54,297
John's mother came up once a month.

650
00:43:58,676 --> 00:44:00,386
But no one could stop Father
Bobby from visiting.

651
00:44:02,639 --> 00:44:05,642
So listen, let's try to keep
this on a happy note, okay?

652
00:44:06,351 --> 00:44:08,895
Nokes warned us not to say
anything to Father Bobby.

653
00:44:09,521 --> 00:44:12,190
If we did, reprisals would be severe.

654
00:44:27,038 --> 00:44:28,581
You lost a few pounds.

655
00:44:29,374 --> 00:44:30,917
It's not exactly home cooking.

656
00:44:32,293 --> 00:44:33,294
Sit down.

657
00:44:34,712 --> 00:44:36,464
This is where I get to see
all four of you guys today.

658
00:44:37,882 --> 00:44:40,635
I loved Father Bobby, but I
couldn't stand to look at him.

659
00:44:41,970 --> 00:44:43,263
I was afraid he'd look
right through me...

660
00:44:43,346 --> 00:44:45,098
...past the fear and shame,
right through to the truth.

661
00:44:45,473 --> 00:44:48,476
Shakes, is there anything
you want to tell me?

662
00:44:50,603 --> 00:44:51,771
Anything at all?

663
00:44:54,148 --> 00:44:55,525
You shouldn't come here anymore, Father.

664
00:44:58,278 --> 00:44:59,904
I appreciate it and all, but...

665
00:45:00,989 --> 00:45:02,782
...I don't think it's the
right thing for you to do.

666
00:45:27,807 --> 00:45:31,019
I stopped off at Attica today on my
way up here to see an old friend.

667
00:45:32,478 --> 00:45:33,938
You have any friends not in jail?

668
00:45:36,232 --> 00:45:37,483
Not as many as I would like.

669
00:45:39,027 --> 00:45:40,320
What's he in for?

670
00:45:41,988 --> 00:45:45,742
Triple murder. He killed three
men about fifteen years ago.

671
00:45:47,243 --> 00:45:48,203
And he's a good friend?

672
00:45:49,162 --> 00:45:49,996
He's my best friend.

673
00:45:52,999 --> 00:45:54,042
We hung out together.

674
00:45:54,751 --> 00:45:57,086
We were close...
just like you and the guys.

675
00:46:09,474 --> 00:46:10,892
We were both sent up here.

676
00:46:14,646 --> 00:46:19,317
That's right. And it wasn't easy...

677
00:46:21,194 --> 00:46:23,404
...just like it's not easy
for you and the guys.

678
00:46:25,949 --> 00:46:29,536
This place killed him...
made him not care anymore.

679
00:46:34,249 --> 00:46:36,668
Don't let this place do
that to you, Shakes.

680
00:46:37,794 --> 00:46:40,088
Don't let it make you think
you're tougher than you are.

681
00:46:41,089 --> 00:46:43,091
I've got to go, Father.

682
00:46:51,641 --> 00:46:52,767
I'll see you in the Kitchen.

683
00:46:55,103 --> 00:46:56,145
I'm counting on you.

684
00:46:58,648 --> 00:47:00,775
Wipe the tears off your face.
Don't let them see it.

685
00:47:01,985 --> 00:47:05,655
Don't let them see you crying.
Don't give them the satisfaction.

686
00:47:08,992 --> 00:47:10,451
You'll be out of here
before you know it.

687
00:47:14,372 --> 00:47:15,540
You're gonna be okay.

688
00:47:22,630 --> 00:47:24,632
I didn't want to let him go.

689
00:47:25,008 --> 00:47:27,510
I never felt as close to anyone
as I felt to him at that moment.

690
00:47:35,018 --> 00:47:37,687
A number of the inmates, as tough as
they acted during the day...

691
00:47:37,854 --> 00:47:39,731
...would often cry themselves
to sleep at night.

692
00:47:40,899 --> 00:47:42,233
There were other cries, too.

693
00:47:43,067 --> 00:47:45,361
These differed from those
filled with fear and loneliness.

694
00:47:46,070 --> 00:47:49,657
They were lower and muffled;
the sounds of pained anguish.

695
00:47:51,034 --> 00:47:53,453
Those cries can change
the course of a life.

696
00:47:54,120 --> 00:47:57,081
They are cries that, once heard,
can never be erased from memory.

697
00:47:57,582 --> 00:48:00,418
On this one night, those cries
belonged to my friend, John...

698
00:48:00,877 --> 00:48:02,837
...when Ralph Ferguson
paid him a visit.

699
00:48:19,771 --> 00:48:22,440
I was expecting to read 30
book reports over the weekend.

700
00:48:22,815 --> 00:48:26,319
There are only 6 for me to read...
which means I'm missing how many?

701
00:48:27,987 --> 00:48:31,157
This is English class.
Math is down the hall.

702
00:48:35,119 --> 00:48:37,997
I want to help you.
You may not believe that.

703
00:48:38,665 --> 00:48:40,166
Or you may not care, but it's the truth.

704
00:48:48,091 --> 00:48:50,760
-You got a second?
-What, I do something wrong?

705
00:48:51,344 --> 00:48:53,763
No. You did a great
job on your book report.

706
00:48:56,099 --> 00:48:58,852
You really seemed to like the book,
"The Count of Monte Cristo."

707
00:48:59,018 --> 00:49:02,355
It's my favourite.
I like it more since I've been here.

708
00:49:03,147 --> 00:49:03,773
Why is that?

709
00:49:05,358 --> 00:49:08,987
It's like... he wouldn't let
anyone beat him, the Count.

710
00:49:09,320 --> 00:49:13,658
Took what he had to take,
beatings, insults and whatever.

711
00:49:14,701 --> 00:49:15,702
And he learned from it.

712
00:49:16,786 --> 00:49:19,998
Then when the time came for him to
do something, he made his move.

713
00:49:21,666 --> 00:49:24,460
-You admire that?
-No, I respect that.

714
00:49:26,337 --> 00:49:28,173
You got a copy of the book at home?

715
00:49:29,007 --> 00:49:30,675
I got the Classics Illustrated Comic.

716
00:49:31,718 --> 00:49:33,011
No, it's not the same thing.

717
00:49:33,803 --> 00:49:36,014
Listen, I gotta go.
I'm gonna miss morning roll call.

718
00:49:36,306 --> 00:49:38,850
I've got something for you.

719
00:49:40,768 --> 00:49:42,061
I thought you might like to have it.

720
00:49:43,062 --> 00:49:44,022
Are you serious?

721
00:49:44,480 --> 00:49:47,025
Well, you love the book that much.
You should have a copy of your own.

722
00:49:47,650 --> 00:49:50,111
-I can't pay you.
-It's a gift.

723
00:49:51,279 --> 00:49:52,614
You've gotten gifts before,
haven't you?

724
00:49:52,780 --> 00:49:53,865
It's been a while.

725
00:49:55,074 --> 00:49:58,411
-Well, it's my way of saying, thanks.
-For what?

726
00:49:59,579 --> 00:50:02,248
That somebody listens...
even if it's just one student.

727
00:50:03,124 --> 00:50:04,501
You're a good teacher, Mr. Carlson.

728
00:50:04,584 --> 00:50:06,794
Listen, we can discuss the book
on Friday in class if you...

729
00:50:07,212 --> 00:50:08,713
...think the Count can
hold their attention.

730
00:50:09,047 --> 00:50:10,215
He's got a shot.

731
00:50:11,049 --> 00:50:12,342
Any particular section
I should read from?

732
00:50:13,092 --> 00:50:15,762
That's easy... the part where
he escapes from prison.

733
00:50:29,442 --> 00:50:32,278
There you go, All Star.
Here's your locker room!

734
00:50:39,827 --> 00:50:44,332
It was only a game... just a touch
football game, nothing more.

735
00:50:45,166 --> 00:50:46,918
But a game I wish we
had never played.

736
00:50:47,961 --> 00:50:51,798
Guards against inmates.
The guards practiced four times a week.

737
00:50:52,632 --> 00:50:54,801
Our team was picked the
Monday before the game.

738
00:50:55,510 --> 00:50:57,011
We had a 2 hour practice.

739
00:50:57,929 --> 00:50:59,138
It didn't matter much.

740
00:50:59,514 --> 00:51:02,517
We weren't supposed to win.
We were just supposed to show up.

741
00:51:03,184 --> 00:51:04,644
Who's the toughest guy here?

742
00:51:05,645 --> 00:51:06,855
How do you mean, tough?

743
00:51:07,355 --> 00:51:09,023
Who can talk and have
everyone listening?

744
00:51:09,190 --> 00:51:11,192
Rizzo. Black kid over there.

745
00:51:13,152 --> 00:51:16,656
Michael saw an opening... a chance
to bring the game to our level.

746
00:51:16,823 --> 00:51:20,827
Even out the field. But he needed help.
He needed Rizzo.

747
00:51:21,661 --> 00:51:25,748
Black kid with an Italian name.
With him on our side, we had a chance.

748
00:51:26,666 --> 00:51:29,669
Look, white boy, I don't know
what you play in the streets.

749
00:51:29,836 --> 00:51:32,088
I don't care. But in here,
the guards call the play...

750
00:51:32,255 --> 00:51:33,882
...and the play calls for
them to win the game.

751
00:51:33,965 --> 00:51:34,716
Why?

752
00:51:35,049 --> 00:51:36,050
Look man...

753
00:51:36,551 --> 00:51:38,052
...guards stay clear of me, all right?

754
00:51:38,219 --> 00:51:39,721
They stay back and let me do my time.

755
00:51:40,054 --> 00:51:41,890
If I play that game and I
put a hurt on one of them...

756
00:51:42,056 --> 00:51:43,683
...they just might change my cushion.

757
00:51:43,892 --> 00:51:47,061
I'm not saying we gotta win.
I just don't want to take a beating.

758
00:51:47,604 --> 00:51:48,563
You do every day.

759
00:51:49,272 --> 00:51:52,567
-Why is Saturday special?
-'Cause on Saturday, we can hit back.

760
00:51:55,737 --> 00:51:58,781
They don't fuck with you like they do us,
but they fuck with you another way!

761
00:51:58,948 --> 00:52:00,200
You're just an animal to them.

762
00:52:01,367 --> 00:52:04,037
-I don't give a fuck!
-Yeah, you do.

763
00:52:04,412 --> 00:52:06,915
And beating them on Saturday
is not gonna change a thing.

764
00:52:07,790 --> 00:52:08,958
Then why, white boy, why?

765
00:52:09,125 --> 00:52:13,505
To make them feel what we feel
...just for a couple of hours.

766
00:52:15,715 --> 00:52:17,509
Now, don't try anything funny, Sambo.

767
00:52:17,717 --> 00:52:19,844
Nobody will get hurt.
You know what I'm saying?

768
00:52:20,261 --> 00:52:21,179
I call heads.

769
00:52:24,307 --> 00:52:26,309
He called heads.
It is a head.

770
00:52:28,269 --> 00:52:29,187
Let's go.

771
00:52:39,447 --> 00:52:42,784
You're gonna die, mother fucker!
You're gonna fucking die!

772
00:52:53,503 --> 00:52:55,505
None of you motherfuckers can cover me!

773
00:52:55,839 --> 00:52:59,175
We got ourselves a game!
I'm feeling good today.

774
00:52:59,676 --> 00:53:00,844
This shit feels good.

775
00:53:07,892 --> 00:53:08,852
Fuck!

776
00:53:15,275 --> 00:53:17,277
Get the fuck off me!

777
00:53:28,580 --> 00:53:31,374
Yeah, keep smiling, you little piss ant.

778
00:53:34,377 --> 00:53:37,046
For 90 minutes, we took
the game out of the prison...

779
00:53:37,672 --> 00:53:39,591
...moved it miles beyond
the locked gates...

780
00:53:39,757 --> 00:53:41,885
...and the sloping hills of
the surrounding countryside...

781
00:53:42,510 --> 00:53:45,305
...and brought it back down to the streets
of the neighbourhoods we'd come from.

782
00:53:46,556 --> 00:53:49,392
For those 90 minutes,
we were once again free!

783
00:54:08,244 --> 00:54:09,746
Rizzo! Rizzo!

784
00:54:21,674 --> 00:54:25,470
Rizzo... Rizzo.

785
00:54:27,180 --> 00:54:30,350
Hey, Nokes.
Good game.

786
00:54:33,269 --> 00:54:36,606
For once, we had a victory.
But it didn't last.

787
00:54:37,273 --> 00:54:41,611
It couldn't last...
and all I wanted to do was die.

788
00:54:42,695 --> 00:54:46,699
I was not alone in the hole. I knew my
friends were down in the depths with me.

789
00:54:47,242 --> 00:54:51,538
Each in his own cell, each in his own
pain... suffering his own demons.

790
00:54:52,163 --> 00:54:53,289
Rizzo was there, too.

791
00:54:56,334 --> 00:54:58,002
I had lost any sense of time.

792
00:55:38,877 --> 00:55:40,044
I thought you'd never wake up.

793
00:55:41,379 --> 00:55:42,714
I thought I'd never want to.

794
00:55:43,089 --> 00:55:46,259
John and Tommy, they're
on the other side there.

795
00:55:47,802 --> 00:55:51,472
How are they?
They're alive.

796
00:55:53,266 --> 00:55:54,267
Who isn't?

797
00:55:56,227 --> 00:55:57,187
Rizzo.

798
00:55:59,898 --> 00:56:01,065
They killed him?

799
00:56:03,067 --> 00:56:07,280
They took turns beating him until
there was nothing of that kid to beat.

800
00:56:12,202 --> 00:56:13,620
Rizzo was dead because of us.

801
00:56:15,038 --> 00:56:17,040
We made him think that going
up against the guards...

802
00:56:17,123 --> 00:56:18,541
...in a meaningless football game...

803
00:56:18,708 --> 00:56:22,295
...had some value... that it would
give us a reason to go on.

804
00:56:23,463 --> 00:56:25,173
Once again, we were wrong.

805
00:56:28,343 --> 00:56:29,677
Did they give you
your release date yet?

806
00:56:29,844 --> 00:56:31,179
Nokes had a letter from the warden.

807
00:56:32,013 --> 00:56:33,890
Waved it in front of me,
then tore it up...

808
00:56:35,058 --> 00:56:35,892
When do you figure?

809
00:56:37,685 --> 00:56:39,896
End of spring, early
summer or something.

810
00:56:40,980 --> 00:56:42,524
I wish we were coming with you.

811
00:56:43,566 --> 00:56:45,902
It would've been nice for all
of us to walk out together.

812
00:56:46,903 --> 00:56:50,240
No use thinking about that. We're
gonna do a full year, not an hour less.

813
00:56:52,283 --> 00:56:55,620
When I get out, I could get Father
Bobby to make a couple of phone calls.

814
00:56:55,828 --> 00:56:57,247
Shave a month or two off.

815
00:56:57,413 --> 00:57:00,083
-There's nothing to talk about!
-There's a lot to talk about.

816
00:57:00,583 --> 00:57:03,503
Maybe, if people knew what was going
on in here, they'd make a move.

817
00:57:04,087 --> 00:57:05,755
I don't want anybody to know.

818
00:57:06,548 --> 00:57:10,260
Not Father Bobby, King Benny,
Fat Mancho...

819
00:57:10,426 --> 00:57:12,762
...not my mother. Nobody.

820
00:57:14,389 --> 00:57:15,932
I don't either.

821
00:57:16,015 --> 00:57:18,268
I mean, I wouldn't know what
to say to anyone who did know.

822
00:57:18,977 --> 00:57:21,646
I can't think of anybody
who needs to hear about it.

823
00:57:22,814 --> 00:57:25,358
Either they won't believe it,
or they won't give a shit.

824
00:57:26,317 --> 00:57:28,611
Yeah, I don't even think we should
talk about it once it's over.

825
00:57:30,947 --> 00:57:34,951
We got no choice but to live with it.
And talking makes living it harder.

826
00:57:36,327 --> 00:57:38,496
So, we might as well
not even talk about it.

827
00:57:39,497 --> 00:57:40,832
The truth stays with us.

828
00:57:44,002 --> 00:57:45,837
I want to be able to sleep one night...

829
00:57:47,380 --> 00:57:50,967
...and not have to worry who's coming
in my room, what's gonna happen to me.

830
00:57:54,721 --> 00:57:58,683
If I can get that, then I'll be happy.

831
00:58:01,352 --> 00:58:04,147
Someday, John, I promise.

832
00:58:20,830 --> 00:58:24,334
I was in my last hours as an inmate
at the Wilkinson Home for boys.

833
00:58:25,168 --> 00:58:27,086
I was given four copies
of my release form.

834
00:58:27,462 --> 00:58:29,756
The final reminder of my
time at Wilkinson.

835
00:58:32,217 --> 00:58:33,801
I never heard the key
turn in the lock...

836
00:58:34,385 --> 00:58:36,471
...and I never heard
the snap of the bolt.

837
00:58:37,972 --> 00:58:39,307
You should be asleep.

838
00:58:40,558 --> 00:58:44,604
I just wanted to say goodbye.
We all do.

839
00:58:47,607 --> 00:58:49,609
I told him. I told him right
to his face. I said,

840
00:58:49,776 --> 00:58:51,611
I don't care if you're paying me
overtime or not.

841
00:58:51,694 --> 00:58:53,238
I'm not working those kind of hours.

842
00:58:53,446 --> 00:58:54,781
Yeah, did you put in for it?

843
00:58:55,281 --> 00:58:56,241
I put in for it!

844
00:58:56,282 --> 00:58:57,992
Because I put in for it.
They don't give it to me.

845
00:58:58,618 --> 00:59:01,829
I come in early for three days.
Do they give me overtime? No!

846
00:59:02,997 --> 00:59:04,958
A part of all of us was
left there that night.

847
00:59:06,000 --> 00:59:08,336
That night will never be
removed from my mind.

848
00:59:08,920 --> 00:59:13,466
The night of June 1, 1968--
the Summer of Love.

849
00:59:15,134 --> 00:59:17,136
My last night at the
Wilkinson Home for boys.

850
01:00:03,808 --> 01:00:06,477
At 8:25 p.m. two men
walked through the doors.

851
01:00:07,478 --> 01:00:10,565
The bartender knew their faces as most
of the neighbourhood knew their names.

852
01:00:10,982 --> 01:00:13,610
They were two of the founding
members of the West Side Boys.

853
01:00:13,693 --> 01:00:15,195
They were also its deadliest.

854
01:00:17,280 --> 01:00:20,283
The blond-haired man had been in and out
of jail since he was a teenager.

855
01:00:20,867 --> 01:00:22,952
He robbed and killed
at will or on command.

856
01:00:23,786 --> 01:00:26,456
He was presently a suspect in
four unsolved homicides.

857
01:00:27,040 --> 01:00:30,627
He was an alcoholic and a cocaine abuser
with a fast temper and a faster trigger.

858
01:00:31,085 --> 01:00:33,922
He once shot a mechanic dead for
moving ahead of him in a movie line.

859
01:00:36,216 --> 01:00:38,218
The dark-haired man was equally deadly...

860
01:00:38,259 --> 01:00:40,553
...and had committed his
first murder at the age of 17.

861
01:00:41,429 --> 01:00:45,266
In return, he was paid $50.
He drank, and he did drugs...

862
01:00:45,433 --> 01:00:48,561
...and he had a wife he never saw,
living somewhere in Queens.

863
01:00:51,272 --> 01:00:54,692
He's making a noble attempt
to really change things.

864
01:00:54,776 --> 01:00:58,446
-The Republicans will take the House.
-Well, we got a lot of work to do.

865
01:00:58,571 --> 01:01:00,240
It's gonna take more
than 4 years to get...

866
01:01:00,406 --> 01:01:01,616
They'll take it at
the mid-term elections.

867
01:01:02,116 --> 01:01:04,953
He's got the charisma.
He's gonna do it.

868
01:01:05,161 --> 01:01:07,830
He's our man. Reagan's
the man who's gonna do it.

869
01:01:09,457 --> 01:01:11,668
Hey, Jerry...
What are they talking about?

870
01:01:12,085 --> 01:01:14,087
They're talking about Reagan's speech.

871
01:01:17,090 --> 01:01:19,592
Order those two men some
drinks and put it on my tab.

872
01:01:21,511 --> 01:01:24,347
You tell them that Republicans
are not welcome in Hell's Kitchen...

873
01:01:24,514 --> 01:01:28,017
...and either a political conversion or
a change of conversation is in order.

874
01:01:28,434 --> 01:01:29,435
Sure thing.

875
01:01:36,484 --> 01:01:39,404
The gentlemen there would like to
buy you a drink on one condition.

876
01:01:39,696 --> 01:01:43,408
You know the rules:
no religion, no politics.

877
01:01:44,033 --> 01:01:45,159
You get my meaning?

878
01:02:03,052 --> 01:02:05,346
Order something for me.
I gotta go to the bathroom.

879
01:02:36,211 --> 01:02:37,337
Can I help you with something, chief?

880
01:02:39,214 --> 01:02:43,593
Not right now.
Enjoy the rest of your meal.

881
01:03:29,430 --> 01:03:33,643
I ordered brisket on a roll,
with fries and...

882
01:03:35,061 --> 01:03:37,814
...two baskets of soda bread.
I know how you like that shit.

883
01:03:38,940 --> 01:03:39,941
Is that okay by you?

884
01:03:42,318 --> 01:03:45,405
Take a look at the guy at the table.
Take a good look.

885
01:03:57,250 --> 01:03:58,334
Motherfucker.

886
01:04:24,861 --> 01:04:26,446
That's him.

887
01:04:26,738 --> 01:04:28,156
Are you fucking kidding me?

888
01:04:31,701 --> 01:04:32,410
Bingo!

889
01:04:58,144 --> 01:04:59,270
This is amazing.

890
01:04:59,437 --> 01:05:02,106
Hello... it's been a long time!

891
01:05:03,858 --> 01:05:04,943
Who the fuck are you guys?

892
01:05:09,322 --> 01:05:10,907
Who the fuck asked you to sit down?

893
01:05:11,407 --> 01:05:14,494
I thought you'd be happy to see us.
I guess I was wrong.

894
01:05:16,329 --> 01:05:18,748
You know, I thought
you'd do a lot better.

895
01:05:19,415 --> 01:05:21,626
You know, with all that training...
all that time you put in...

896
01:05:22,252 --> 01:05:24,295
...just to end up watching
someone else's money.

897
01:05:24,629 --> 01:05:25,922
That seems like a waste.

898
01:05:26,130 --> 01:05:28,091
I'm asking you now for the last
time, what the fuck do you want?

899
01:05:28,299 --> 01:05:30,009
Why don't you take your time?
It'll come to you.

900
01:05:35,807 --> 01:05:37,600
I can see how he might forget us.

901
01:05:38,268 --> 01:05:41,187
You know, we were just something for
you and your friends to play with.

902
01:05:41,354 --> 01:05:43,481
It's a little harder for us to forget.

903
01:05:43,857 --> 01:05:46,109
You gave us so much more to remember.

904
01:05:49,487 --> 01:05:50,864
You can't quite place us,
can you, chief?

905
01:05:51,614 --> 01:05:55,618
Let me help you out. You're looking
at John Reilly and Tommy Marcano.

906
01:06:07,088 --> 01:06:08,006
Yeah, that's right.

907
01:06:14,804 --> 01:06:16,139
That was a long time ago.

908
01:06:19,684 --> 01:06:20,435
So how you been?

909
01:06:21,436 --> 01:06:22,937
Yeah, we ain't kids now.

910
01:06:24,230 --> 01:06:25,565
So, what do you want?

911
01:06:26,399 --> 01:06:29,736
What I've always wanted
is to watch you die!

912
01:06:35,783 --> 01:06:36,826
You ordered the meat loaf.

913
01:06:38,453 --> 01:06:41,456
The brisket's really good here,
only you'll never know it.

914
01:06:42,749 --> 01:06:43,583
You fucked up.

915
01:06:57,388 --> 01:07:01,726
Yeah, you were scared little pricks,
both of you.

916
01:07:03,269 --> 01:07:07,941
All of you... scared shitless.
But I...

917
01:07:09,859 --> 01:07:13,321
...I tried to make you tough.
I tried to make you hard.

918
01:07:13,363 --> 01:07:16,991
I had you all wrong then, Nokes.
All this time I thought you just liked...

919
01:07:17,158 --> 01:07:18,660
...fucking and beating up little boys.

920
01:07:18,868 --> 01:07:21,120
You two motherfuckers
are gonna burn in hell!

921
01:07:21,704 --> 01:07:23,039
You're gonna burn in hell.

922
01:07:23,206 --> 01:07:24,165
Yeah, after you.

923
01:07:29,963 --> 01:07:31,130
Did that hurt, Nokes?

924
01:08:08,668 --> 01:08:12,922
Jerry, sorry, should've made
those brisket sandwiches to go.

925
01:08:25,518 --> 01:08:26,853
John Reilly, how do you plead?

926
01:08:27,228 --> 01:08:28,396
Not guilty, Your Honour.

927
01:08:29,355 --> 01:08:30,231
Thomas Marcano?

928
01:08:31,733 --> 01:08:32,901
Not guilty, Your Honour.

929
01:08:33,443 --> 01:08:37,155
John Reilly and Thomas Marcano,
you are hereby held without bail.

930
01:08:38,364 --> 01:08:41,784
In all the years since Wilkinson's, we
had never once spoken to each other...

931
01:08:41,951 --> 01:08:45,288
...about what happened there.
We remained caring friends...

932
01:08:45,455 --> 01:08:47,457
...but the relationship
had been altered.

933
01:08:48,625 --> 01:08:52,795
We drifted together, always wondering
if that moment would arrive...

934
01:08:53,254 --> 01:08:55,006
...that would force us to
deal with the past.

935
01:09:08,520 --> 01:09:11,856
One down, Shakes, one down.

936
01:09:13,858 --> 01:09:14,692
One what?

937
01:09:16,945 --> 01:09:20,281
One Sean Nokes.

938
01:09:21,449 --> 01:09:22,325
Nokes?

939
01:09:30,625 --> 01:09:31,876
At the time of Nokes' shooting,

940
01:09:31,918 --> 01:09:34,879
Michael was working as an
Assistant New York District Attorney.

941
01:09:35,338 --> 01:09:38,091
I got a call that he wanted to meet me
on 45th Street in Queens.

942
01:09:38,925 --> 01:09:39,884
Then, he hung up.

943
01:09:44,430 --> 01:09:46,140
-So, what did they say?
-What?

944
01:09:46,391 --> 01:09:47,642
John and Tommy, what'd they say?

945
01:09:47,809 --> 01:09:49,143
It's a little cloak and
dagger, isn't it, Mike?

946
01:09:50,061 --> 01:09:52,063
Nokes?
Did they talk about him?

947
01:09:53,982 --> 01:09:55,316
-John did.
-Yeah?

948
01:09:56,192 --> 01:09:57,193
What did he say?

949
01:09:58,027 --> 01:10:00,655
He said, "One down, Shakes.
One down."

950
01:10:04,200 --> 01:10:06,202
I hear they hired Danny Snyder
as the lawyer, is that right?

951
01:10:06,369 --> 01:10:08,872
It's temporary. King Benny's
gonna move in one of his lawyers.

952
01:10:09,122 --> 01:10:11,791
Don't let him do that.
Snyder's perfect.

953
01:10:12,041 --> 01:10:14,419
-Perfect? The guy's a fall down drunk!
-Then he is perfect.

954
01:10:14,919 --> 01:10:16,045
Perfect for what?

955
01:10:20,091 --> 01:10:21,926
Are you covering this
story for your newspaper?

956
01:10:22,093 --> 01:10:23,094
-Me?
-Yeah.

957
01:10:23,428 --> 01:10:27,098
I'm a timetable clerk, Mikey. Ask me
what movie's playing at what time.

958
01:10:27,265 --> 01:10:28,224
I'm lucky they let me in the building.

959
01:10:33,271 --> 01:10:34,105
Get some coffee?

960
01:10:35,148 --> 01:10:36,107
Let's take a walk.

961
01:10:47,118 --> 01:10:48,953
I'm gonna prosecute John
and Tommy in an open court.

962
01:10:50,371 --> 01:10:51,831
What, are you fucking nuts?

963
01:10:53,041 --> 01:10:53,708
Just hear me out.

964
01:10:54,083 --> 01:10:56,878
You should stay home tomorrow.
Call in sick and save your life, counsel.

965
01:10:57,045 --> 01:10:58,379
I'm not taking this case to win.

966
01:10:59,923 --> 01:11:01,591
I'm taking this case to lose.

967
01:11:03,009 --> 01:11:03,843
What does that mean?

968
01:11:06,262 --> 01:11:07,847
It means it's payback time.

969
01:11:08,973 --> 01:11:13,394
Look, John and Tommy started this.
It's begun.

970
01:11:14,145 --> 01:11:17,524
It's messy, it's not how I had
it planned but... here it is.

971
01:11:18,983 --> 01:11:21,653
And you and l, we can finish it.

972
01:11:22,529 --> 01:11:23,780
Finish what, Mikey?

973
01:11:26,157 --> 01:11:27,992
You read "The Count of
Monte Cristo" lately?

974
01:11:29,827 --> 01:11:31,913
I don't know... ten years ago.

975
01:11:33,081 --> 01:11:35,416
You see, I read a little
bit of it every night.

976
01:11:36,543 --> 01:11:40,755
I read words like 'revenge'.
Sweet, lasting revenge.

977
01:11:42,924 --> 01:11:44,467
Payback time.

978
01:11:46,302 --> 01:11:47,637
It's our time.

979
01:11:48,429 --> 01:11:49,681
What are you saying, Mike?

980
01:11:50,640 --> 01:11:53,434
I'm saying it's time for
all of us to get a taste.

981
01:11:55,228 --> 01:11:57,230
I'm saying it's time
to put an end to this.

982
01:11:59,399 --> 01:12:00,441
Let's walk.

983
01:12:04,320 --> 01:12:05,780
So, I asked for the case.

984
01:12:05,864 --> 01:12:07,824
I told them I was from the same
neighbourhood as the accused...

985
01:12:07,991 --> 01:12:09,993
...knew the mentality of the area,
blah, blah, blah...

986
01:12:10,285 --> 01:12:11,160
They bought it.

987
01:12:12,036 --> 01:12:14,122
And the connection between
John, Tommy and Nokes?

988
01:12:14,622 --> 01:12:17,417
What connection? All juvenile records
are destroyed after seven years.

989
01:12:18,376 --> 01:12:20,044
We were never at Wilkinson's.

990
01:12:23,631 --> 01:12:26,176
We gotta go after the guards.
I gotta get Wilkinson's.

991
01:12:27,594 --> 01:12:28,469
Bring it all down.

992
01:12:29,304 --> 01:12:32,473
Adam Styler, plain-clothes cop,
works narcotics in Queens.

993
01:12:32,765 --> 01:12:36,269
Known to shake down dealers for dope
and cash. He's got a cocaine problem.

994
01:12:36,519 --> 01:12:38,104
Other personal information there.

995
01:12:38,438 --> 01:12:41,774
Henry Addison now works for the Mayor,
if you can fucking believe that.

996
01:12:42,275 --> 01:12:43,985
He's a Community Outreach
Director in Brooklyn.

997
01:12:44,319 --> 01:12:48,281
His sexual habits haven't changed.
He still likes sex with young boys.

998
01:12:48,531 --> 01:12:51,701
Ralph Ferguson works in a Social
Service agency in Long Island.

999
01:12:51,951 --> 01:12:53,369
How long have you been
working on this, Mike?

1000
01:12:53,453 --> 01:12:55,663
He's recently divorced, got
one child, and on weekends...

1001
01:12:55,955 --> 01:12:57,498
...teaches Catholic Sunday school.

1002
01:12:57,957 --> 01:12:59,292
Well, he seems clean then, right?

1003
01:12:59,501 --> 01:13:01,377
That's exactly why I
want the piece of shit.

1004
01:13:02,045 --> 01:13:04,797
The plan is to call Ferguson
in as a character witness.

1005
01:13:04,964 --> 01:13:07,133
Get him talking about his
best friend, Sean Nokes.

1006
01:13:07,509 --> 01:13:11,304
Once I got him on the stand, I'm
gonna open the door to Wilkinson's.

1007
01:13:12,180 --> 01:13:16,392
Mike, are you sure you
want to go this way?

1008
01:13:19,812 --> 01:13:21,814
I mean, we buried this a long time ago.

1009
01:13:24,317 --> 01:13:25,818
Do you still sleep with the light on?

1010
01:13:31,574 --> 01:13:34,619
John and Tommy, do you want them
to know anything about this?

1011
01:13:35,036 --> 01:13:36,621
No, it'll play better in
court if they don't know.

1012
01:13:49,717 --> 01:13:52,804
The 'not guilty' verdict had to be a
verdict that no one would dare question.

1013
01:13:53,596 --> 01:13:56,099
Danny Snyder was to remain as
Tommy and John's attorney.

1014
01:13:57,725 --> 01:13:59,561
Michael's plan relied heavily
on Hell's Kitchen...

1015
01:13:59,644 --> 01:14:01,563
...to deliver information and keep quiet.

1016
01:14:02,146 --> 01:14:04,107
Both were skills the Neighbourhood
had in abundance.

1017
01:14:04,941 --> 01:14:06,943
We'd set up a simple
method of communication.

1018
01:14:07,485 --> 01:14:09,946
If Michael was sending,
messages were left at work...

1019
01:14:10,113 --> 01:14:12,282
...for me to call my non-existent
girlfriend, "Gloria".

1020
01:14:12,991 --> 01:14:16,327
If I needed to get word to Michael, I'd
have someone from the neighbourhood...

1021
01:14:16,494 --> 01:14:18,162
...pick up an early edition
of the New York Times...

1022
01:14:18,580 --> 01:14:21,499
...write the word "Edmund" in the upper
right hand corner of the Metro section...

1023
01:14:21,791 --> 01:14:23,501
...and drop it in front
of Michael's apartment.

1024
01:14:28,882 --> 01:14:29,674
For this plan to succeed...

1025
01:14:29,757 --> 01:14:32,760
...we needed total secrecy of
the only people we completely trusted.

1026
01:14:33,386 --> 01:14:35,388
The plan depended on
keeping Michael alive...

1027
01:14:35,763 --> 01:14:37,974
...which meant that word had to get
to John and Tommy's killing crew...

1028
01:14:38,057 --> 01:14:39,350
...that he was not an open target.

1029
01:14:39,893 --> 01:14:43,229
After this night, Michael would
not be available to any of us.

1030
01:14:43,479 --> 01:14:45,648
The only time we would see
him would be in court.

1031
01:14:46,524 --> 01:14:47,859
-That's it?
-Not quite.

1032
01:14:48,443 --> 01:14:51,863
We've got four witnesses who saw the
shooting and are willing to testify.

1033
01:14:52,113 --> 01:14:52,989
Gotta get that number down.

1034
01:14:53,531 --> 01:14:55,533
-I'll talk to King Benny.
-Good.

1035
01:14:56,701 --> 01:15:00,205
I can handle two, but...
you gotta get us one for our side.

1036
01:15:00,705 --> 01:15:02,665
-One of what?
-One witness.

1037
01:15:03,291 --> 01:15:06,169
A witness who'll put John & Tommy
elsewhere on the night of the murder.

1038
01:15:07,003 --> 01:15:08,546
A witness they can't touch.

1039
01:15:10,215 --> 01:15:11,508
Don't they have a name for that?

1040
01:15:12,467 --> 01:15:13,801
A judge would call it perjury.

1041
01:15:15,553 --> 01:15:16,679
And what are we calling it?

1042
01:15:17,055 --> 01:15:18,181
A favour.

1043
01:15:21,511 --> 01:15:22,179
Get up!

1044
01:15:25,849 --> 01:15:27,392
-Tony!
-Yeah, King?

1045
01:15:27,809 --> 01:15:29,603
Bring Danny Snyder to see me.

1046
01:15:30,187 --> 01:15:31,521
Who? Danny Snyder, the lawyer?

1047
01:15:31,688 --> 01:15:33,357
You know more than one Danny Snyder?

1048
01:15:34,733 --> 01:15:36,068
Bring me the one you know.

1049
01:15:55,087 --> 01:15:59,424
I can't do this now, you gotta know that.
It's been a long time for me.

1050
01:16:01,927 --> 01:16:05,264
You need somebody younger, you know.
Somebody like I used to be.

1051
01:16:05,806 --> 01:16:06,974
Younger is not better.

1052
01:16:07,683 --> 01:16:11,270
Doesn't have experience, doesn't
know its way around a courthouse.

1053
01:16:11,478 --> 01:16:13,313
Yeah, I'm lucky I can
find the courthouse.

1054
01:16:15,107 --> 01:16:18,610
I had only four cases last year.
You know how many I won?

1055
01:16:19,486 --> 01:16:22,155
None. That's how many. None.

1056
01:16:23,448 --> 01:16:26,535
In two of them, I think the...

1057
01:16:26,785 --> 01:16:28,370
...the jury blamed me personally.

1058
01:16:28,954 --> 01:16:29,955
They must've been innocent.

1059
01:16:31,456 --> 01:16:34,376
It's tough to get
innocent men off a rap.

1060
01:16:34,793 --> 01:16:37,004
I wasn't even planning on
going to court with this one.

1061
01:16:37,170 --> 01:16:40,132
I was just gonna plea it down
best I could and walk away.

1062
01:16:40,299 --> 01:16:43,051
I wasn't planning on
taking this to trial, sir.

1063
01:16:43,385 --> 01:16:45,387
Well, your plans have been changed.

1064
01:16:45,846 --> 01:16:49,766
Well, I am afraid that I'll make a
mistake and say the wrong thing...

1065
01:16:52,019 --> 01:16:55,063
...make a wrong turn somewhere.
And you don't want to take that risk.

1066
01:16:55,397 --> 01:16:56,732
Life is risk.

1067
01:16:57,024 --> 01:16:57,900
I'm sorry.

1068
01:16:58,233 --> 01:16:59,568
Life is risk.

1069
01:17:00,152 --> 01:17:01,153
Life is a risk?

1070
01:17:05,824 --> 01:17:07,326
I haven't been in here before.

1071
01:17:09,536 --> 01:17:10,871
What do you need me to do?

1072
01:17:12,039 --> 01:17:15,375
You're gonna be given the
answers and the questions.

1073
01:17:16,543 --> 01:17:20,005
All you have to do is read.
You can read, can't you?

1074
01:17:21,215 --> 01:17:22,549
Is it in English?

1075
01:17:22,716 --> 01:17:25,636
Just don't drift, don't drink,
and don't lose.

1076
01:17:27,262 --> 01:17:28,388
What if I do lose?

1077
01:17:28,764 --> 01:17:30,891
Then you'll go down for the dirt nap.

1078
01:17:32,100 --> 01:17:33,894
Never heard that expression before.

1079
01:17:36,271 --> 01:17:36,939
Dirt nap.

1080
01:17:39,066 --> 01:17:43,278
I'm not really cut out for this anymore.
I mean, a guy gets hit by a bus...

1081
01:17:43,987 --> 01:17:46,615
...and sues, I like that.

1082
01:17:46,782 --> 01:17:50,577
Some lady slips in a supermarket...
I'm with her.

1083
01:17:50,744 --> 01:17:52,246
The discussion is over.

1084
01:17:52,538 --> 01:17:56,333
I'm an alcoholic. This is a murder case.
This isn't for me.

1085
01:17:56,500 --> 01:17:57,668
It was once.

1086
01:17:58,752 --> 01:18:00,337
Before you let the drink lead.

1087
01:18:01,838 --> 01:18:05,676
Be sober by tomorrow.
And don't look so worried, Snyder.

1088
01:18:06,343 --> 01:18:08,887
You've got nothing to lose...
just like the rest of us.

1089
01:18:09,805 --> 01:18:12,683
I don't want to be a burden
to you, but I...

1090
01:18:13,517 --> 01:18:17,896
...along with my alcohol problem,
I have a slight drug problem.

1091
01:18:18,063 --> 01:18:19,064
I mean, nothing big.

1092
01:18:19,940 --> 01:18:20,649
Go away.

1093
01:18:31,702 --> 01:18:33,328
Within days of Michael taking the case...

1094
01:18:33,412 --> 01:18:35,581
...the West Side Boys got a visit
from King Benny.

1095
01:18:36,206 --> 01:18:39,418
The King requested that the verbal abuse
directed towards Michael continue.

1096
01:18:39,877 --> 01:18:43,213
"Traitor" and "gutter rat" were
heard up and down the avenue.

1097
01:18:43,380 --> 01:18:45,549
But there was never to be
a death move against him.

1098
01:18:46,174 --> 01:18:50,012
The hit on Michael Sullivan, if there was
one, could only come from King Benny.

1099
01:18:50,429 --> 01:18:52,890
The underground word...
the only one that mattered...

1100
01:18:53,098 --> 01:18:55,434
...had spread through the streets with
the speed of a late-night bullet.

1101
01:19:00,230 --> 01:19:02,441
King Benny's sleepers
were making their play.

1102
01:19:03,442 --> 01:19:07,404
"Sleepers" was a street name for anyone
who spent time in a juvenile facility.

1103
01:19:18,081 --> 01:19:19,708
You gonna pay for that,
you little prick?

1104
01:19:20,125 --> 01:19:23,128
Need your help, fat man.
Need a big favour.

1105
01:19:23,212 --> 01:19:24,338
I'll be outside.

1106
01:19:24,796 --> 01:19:25,839
King Benny been to see you?

1107
01:19:26,048 --> 01:19:27,174
Oh, my goodness!

1108
01:19:27,758 --> 01:19:29,885
What a fucking thing we put together!

1109
01:19:30,135 --> 01:19:34,514
You have a drunk lawyer on one side,
a kid lawyer on the other.

1110
01:19:34,848 --> 01:19:37,351
Fucking paper boy,
making like Dick Tracy.

1111
01:19:38,352 --> 01:19:41,021
There are four sets of eyeballs
that saw the whole thing!

1112
01:19:42,314 --> 01:19:45,108
Meanwhile, the two on trial
kill more people than cancer.

1113
01:19:45,651 --> 01:19:47,861
Fucking General Custer has
a better shot at a walk!

1114
01:19:48,028 --> 01:19:49,780
There's no connection
with the guard and us.

1115
01:19:49,947 --> 01:19:51,823
The cops think it's a
drug-related homicide.

1116
01:19:51,990 --> 01:19:53,825
It's just we need you to
pull a few strings, fat man.

1117
01:19:54,159 --> 01:19:57,162
You know, if you get caught on this,
you're looking straight at serious.

1118
01:19:57,663 --> 01:19:59,498
I'm talking real jail.
The big house...

1119
01:20:07,047 --> 01:20:08,799
They are not good boys any more.

1120
01:20:09,633 --> 01:20:12,970
They're killers now.
Cold as stone.

1121
01:20:14,680 --> 01:20:15,764
I know.

1122
01:20:16,431 --> 01:20:19,268
I know what they were, and I know
what they are, and it's not about that.

1123
01:20:19,434 --> 01:20:23,063
It's not worth it, throwing
away life just to get even.

1124
01:20:24,523 --> 01:20:26,525
You and the lawyer have
a chance to get out.

1125
01:20:26,817 --> 01:20:27,859
To get out the right way.

1126
01:20:28,110 --> 01:20:30,529
There's no choice... not for us.

1127
01:20:34,992 --> 01:20:36,702
On occasion, I'd have
dinner with Carol.

1128
01:20:37,244 --> 01:20:40,581
She still lived in the neighbourhood and
was a social worker in the South Bronx.

1129
01:20:41,123 --> 01:20:43,792
Her concern for us was undiminished
by the passing years.

1130
01:20:44,877 --> 01:20:47,921
Whenever we went out as a group, Carol
would walk between Michael and John...

1131
01:20:48,380 --> 01:20:49,339
...grasping their arms...

1132
01:20:50,716 --> 01:20:52,885
...in step between the lawyer
and the killer.

1133
01:20:52,968 --> 01:20:56,597
Mug me or marry me, Shakes.
I'm too tired for anything else.

1134
01:20:57,931 --> 01:20:59,558
Would you settle for a
couple of beers, Carol?

1135
01:21:01,435 --> 01:21:03,228
If that's your best offer.

1136
01:21:05,105 --> 01:21:06,231
I'll throw in a hug and a kiss.

1137
01:21:07,608 --> 01:21:08,442
Deal.

1138
01:21:14,489 --> 01:21:15,490
You look tired.

1139
01:21:16,033 --> 01:21:17,034
Thank you.

1140
01:21:18,076 --> 01:21:20,078
They don't give you time to
sleep on this new job of yours?

1141
01:21:24,458 --> 01:21:26,126
So, how much do you know?

1142
01:21:27,502 --> 01:21:28,795
Just what the neighbourhood says.

1143
01:21:30,047 --> 01:21:31,673
And what I read in papers like yours.

1144
01:21:32,674 --> 01:21:34,009
What does the neighbourhood say?

1145
01:21:34,551 --> 01:21:36,136
That they're gonna put
Johnny and Tommy away.

1146
01:21:36,553 --> 01:21:38,472
That their best friend's
gonna be the one to do it.

1147
01:21:38,680 --> 01:21:39,640
You believe that?

1148
01:21:40,057 --> 01:21:41,391
It's hard not to, Shakes.

1149
01:21:41,934 --> 01:21:45,270
Unless we all have it wrong.
He did take the fucking case.

1150
01:21:46,605 --> 01:21:48,607
-He did take the case.
-What else is there to say?

1151
01:21:51,652 --> 01:21:52,736
You know Michael very well...

1152
01:21:53,779 --> 01:21:55,447
...maybe even better than I do.

1153
01:21:55,697 --> 01:21:58,283
Yeah, I thought I did.
Now, I don't know.

1154
01:21:58,492 --> 01:22:00,160
-You do know.
-I don't know!

1155
01:22:01,036 --> 01:22:02,621
He went in there, and
he asked for the case.

1156
01:22:02,829 --> 01:22:04,915
Now, you tell me, what the
hell kind of friend is that?

1157
01:22:05,874 --> 01:22:06,875
The best kind.

1158
01:22:08,293 --> 01:22:10,337
The kind who'll throw away
everything to help his friends.

1159
01:22:14,675 --> 01:22:15,676
What are you telling me, Shakes?

1160
01:22:17,553 --> 01:22:21,014
You know this neighbourhood, Carol.
Everything's a shakedown or a scam.

1161
01:22:21,181 --> 01:22:23,016
Why should this be any different?

1162
01:22:29,606 --> 01:22:30,566
I'm hungry.

1163
01:22:31,817 --> 01:22:33,110
I'm gonna get something to eat.

1164
01:22:35,112 --> 01:22:38,532
There's this point in Michael
that you can't go beyond.

1165
01:22:39,157 --> 01:22:41,618
I mean, you can try. I tried.

1166
01:22:42,619 --> 01:22:45,289
And he just... he shut down.

1167
01:22:45,831 --> 01:22:49,418
Couldn't touch him...
couldn't even breathe on him.

1168
01:22:52,546 --> 01:22:53,463
I thought it was me.

1169
01:22:55,883 --> 01:22:57,759
After a while, it just
gets easier to let it go.

1170
01:22:59,136 --> 01:23:00,053
Do you still love him?

1171
01:23:00,512 --> 01:23:01,680
I don't think about it, Shakes.

1172
01:23:03,557 --> 01:23:05,684
If I did, I'd say 'yes.'

1173
01:23:06,685 --> 01:23:07,561
But you're with John now.

1174
01:23:08,312 --> 01:23:12,482
Yeah... as much as
anybody can be with John.

1175
01:23:14,610 --> 01:23:16,570
The man I know is not
the boy you remember.

1176
01:23:16,778 --> 01:23:17,946
None of us are.

1177
01:23:18,989 --> 01:23:20,949
But there's something
special about John.

1178
01:23:22,868 --> 01:23:24,953
You just have to look a
little harder to see it.

1179
01:23:30,292 --> 01:23:31,793
Why didn't you ever ask me out?

1180
01:23:32,336 --> 01:23:34,171
-Me?
-Yeah.

1181
01:23:35,714 --> 01:23:36,840
Cause you were Mikey's girl.

1182
01:23:39,551 --> 01:23:40,636
He got to you first.

1183
01:23:41,094 --> 01:23:42,262
And after Mikey?

1184
01:23:43,263 --> 01:23:44,264
I think it was Tommy's turn.

1185
01:23:44,890 --> 01:23:46,558
Fuck you!

1186
01:23:49,853 --> 01:23:50,896
Because...

1187
01:23:52,272 --> 01:23:54,107
...I didn't think you'd say 'yes.'

1188
01:24:00,656 --> 01:24:02,324
Well, you were wrong, Shakes.

1189
01:24:03,992 --> 01:24:04,952
You were wrong.

1190
01:24:12,334 --> 01:24:13,502
What? Go ahead and say it.

1191
01:24:15,879 --> 01:24:19,299
You work at Social Services, you
got files. You got access to files.

1192
01:24:20,050 --> 01:24:22,177
And from time to time, we're
